<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt PM Takes Stock of Asian Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri said today that the objective of his Asian tour was
to encourage Asian investors to contribute to Egypt's development
process.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri, who returned home on Tuesday evening from a ten-day
visit to Malaysia, Singapore and China, today gave a detailed
report to President Hosni Mubarak on his appraisal of the outcome
of the tour.
</P>
<P>
"My visit is aimed at boosting relations with the three
countries, discussing issues of common interest and reviewing the
latest developments of the Mideast peace process," Ganzouri told
reporters after the meeting with Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He termed as "fruitful" his tour to the three countries, the
first of its kind by an Egyptian prime minister in 33 years.
</P>
<P>
"I felt the three countries' support for Egypt and its leaders
in serving regional and international causes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Taking stock of Egypt's investment environment, however, he
said that offering tax and customs exemptions is not enough to
lure investors to the country.
</P>
<P>
"What is more important is to solve any problem facing the
investors inside Egypt," he added, voicing the hope that his tour
would be a prelude to other tours of Arab and European countries.
</P>
<P>
He signed a number of agreements with the three governments
while the 25 Egyptian businessmen accompanying him on the visit
also concluded several deals in the fields of exportation and
establishing joint ventures, said the premier.
</P>
<P>
Memorandums of understanding were also concluded to set up
giant projects between Egypt and Singapore, Malaysia and China.
</P>
<P>
"I discussed with Asian officials the possibility of launching
new projects in Egypt, especially establishing free trade zones,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Singapore have agreed in principle to establish the
"Shark-Al-Tafria" free trade zone on a 50-square-kilometer
area, while a Singaporean delegation will visit Egypt in mid-May
for more follow-up talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the prime minister, a Chinese delegation is due
here in mid-June to probe potentials for launching a
Sino-Egyptian free economic zone north of the Gulf of Suez.
</P>
<P>
He said that an agreement was reached with Malaysia on setting
up an agricultural and industrial zone in east al-Oweinat.
</P>
<P>
Since coming to power in January 1996, the government of
Ganzouri has made boosting investment its top priority and vowed
to remove all obstacles to that goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
