<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Japan to Solve Trade Disputes Through Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC),
the executive body of the European Union (EU), and Japan have
agreed not to resort to the World Trade Organization (WTO) dispute
settlement mechanism unless solutions to their trade disputes
cannot be found through bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached the agreement at their annual high level
consultations held in Brussels, where they reviewed bilateral
trade and investment, examined progress towards deregulation in
Japan, and analyzed the current state and prospects for
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Japan has agreed to a fresh round of consultations on fish
products and hoped to work together with the EC to advance Japan's
accession to an agreement on automobile trade.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of objective analysis of trade flows was also
agreed, with the commission suggesting a joint study into the
causes leading to low European investment in Japan.
</P>
<P>
EC also welcomed the dialogue over deregulation in Japan, but
said that progress in this field so far had been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was co-chaired by Hans-Friederich Beseler, the EC's
director-general for external economic relations, and Ogura Kazuo,
vice-minister for foreign affairs of Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
