<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Mobilizes People Against Islamists as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Algerian government has
appealed to the people to mobilize themselves and stay double
vigilant against Islamic extremists, after 93 villagers were
slaughtered Monday night in a remote village 25 kilometers from
the capital Algiers.
</P>
<P>
In a speech Tuesday night on television, Algerian Prime
Minister Ahmed Ouyahia condemned the massacre of the villagers,
half of the victims being women, young girls and children, by what
he called "terrorist dregs who are engaged in a suicidal headlong
rush."
</P>
<P>
He called on the people to show double vigilance and mobilize
themselves against the terrorists, who he said were trying to
sabotage the country's coming legislative elections scheduled for
June 5.
</P>
<P>
"Each time Algeria moves ahead in its process of going out of
the crisis, it meets with a resurgence of terrorist acts, such as
those produced on the eve of the presidential elections (in 1995)
and the referendum on the revision of the constitution (this
year)," said Ouyahia.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian army are distributing leaflets at all the highway
exists of big cities to car drivers, urging those young people who
have supported Islamic extremist groups to abandon "the road of
violence."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all the Algerian political parties, except the
outlawed Islamic Salvation Front (FIS), have registered to join
the legislative elections on June 5, which will produce a new
two-chamber parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian television also showed pictures of some survivors
of the massacre who escaped to the capital Algiers after
witnessing their closest slaughtered in the most atrocious ways by
Islamists.
</P>
<P>
One 14-year-old girl witnessed the terrorists slaughtering her
whole family, while a woman, whose throat was half cut, survived
by pretending to be dead.
</P>
<P>
They said that the terrorists numbered 150 to 200, fully armed,
having beard hanging to their breasts, and some of them showing
the word "emir" in their hair cut.
</P>
<P>
The Islamists placed land mines and explosive engines on the
outskirt of the Haouch-Boukhelef-Khemisti farmstead on the plain
of Mitidja to prevent security forces from rescuing the villagers,
said the survivors.
</P>
<P>
The villagers were killed by knife and agricultural tools, and
some of them were burnt to death, said witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that this is the first time for the Algerian
government to fully publicize a massacre in the village,
apparently because of the seriousness of the latest massacre,
which is the biggest made known since the country was plunged into
violence five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French government today expressed its solidarity
with the Algerian people and condemned the massacre as "an
atrocity beyond imagination."
</P>
<P>
"France is worried and shocked by the blind and savage
character of the violence which is striking Algeria," said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 to 80,000 people are estimated to have been killed
by violence in Algeria over the past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
