<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Rain Over Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- For the next five months, China
will play rainmaker over the upper reaches of the Yellow River to
alleviate the effects of severe drought in the valley.
</P>
<P>
The 5,464-km Yellow River, the second-longest river in China,
rises in the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and has been suffering from
drought since 1990, with less water flowing in the upper reaches
and no flow at all in part of the lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, the water level in the upper
reaches has dropped to its lowest point in history.
</P>
<P>
An area of 30,000 sq km, located among Qinghai, Gansu, and
Sichuan provinces, was chosen as the site for an artificial rain
project, to be carried out by airplanes dropping chemicals into
the clouds to produce precipitation.
</P>
<P>
The one million yuan (about 120,000 US dollars) project will be
carried over the next five months to increase the river's water
volume by 480 million cubic meters, which is 2.2 percent of the
river's annual water flow in Qinghai Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
