<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dini Says EC Forecast "Balanced," "Correct" on Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini said today that the European Commission (EC)'s recent
forecast on Italy's ability to join a single currency Europe is
"correct" and "balanced."
</P>
<P>
Dini made the comment to the press in the German capital of
Bonn while accompanying Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro on
a four-day state visit to Germany.
</P>
<P>
He said the assessments made by the EC, the executive body of
the European Union (EU), on how various countries would meet the
criteria for entrance into the European Monetary Union (EMU) were
"correct."
</P>
<P>
The EMU, set forth by the Maastricht Treaty agreed on by EU
member nations, would launch a single European currency, called
the Euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The "balanced" EC report "fully recognizes all that we are
doing and what we have done," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report's predication that Italy's ratio of
budget deficit against gross domestic product (GDP) would be worse
in 1998 than in 1997, Dini said some of the current budget
measures do not go beyond this year and the 1998 budget would turn
them into more lasting provisions so as to control the deficit/GDP
ratio under the targeted three percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the Italian government is already working on a welfare
reform, so as to reach the goals set by the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
