<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayors Call For Guarding Famous Historical Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The First Mayors' Forum on
Well-Known Chinese Historical and Cultural Cities closed today in
the city of Luoyang, Henan Province, with a call for greater
efforts to protect the country's old towns.
</P>
<P>
The mayors urged all citizens to be aware of the obligation to
safeguard historical cities, and said general planning of these
cities should be well-organized and conducted in accordance with
the law.
</P>
<P>
They also asked that special funds be set up to help, and said
that both the government as well as people at home and from abroad
are asked to contribute financially.
</P>
<P>
China's development should not be done at the cost of
destroying the country's historical and cultural traditions, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which was held over the last three days, was
sponsored by four units including the overseas edition of the
People's Daily and the Luoyang city government. Participants
included mayors from over 20 Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
This is the first such symposium on the development and
protection of old cities in China since the government named 99
cities as famous historical and cultural towns in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
