<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Army Chief Rejects US "Zero Death" Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chief of staff of the French armed
forces General Jean-Philippe Douin has rejected the American
concept of "zero death" in modern military operations, which
emphasizes the role of high technology in military equipment.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the latest issue of the Defense Ministry
publication "Lettre de la Defense," Douin described as "illusion
of military saloon" the concept of "zero death," which claims that
technological superiority in armaments and communications can
bring victory over the enemy with a minimum number of soldiers
deployed.
</P>
<P>
"Technology will never replace engagement in the field, which
always carries risk but is the only way that allows one to obtain
the outcome sought," said the top soldier of the French army.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the French army will always let its soldiers
go into the field under good conditions, which he said is "a very
clear will" of President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
"Our men should be able to defend themselves if the situation
calls for it, by imposing themselves with force and properly
adapted means upon the (other) sides in presence," he said.
</P>
<P>
France now has 15,000 soldiers deployed overseas, most of them
in Africa but also in former Yugoslavia and Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
