<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Court Gives Jail Sentences to Skinheads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A court in the French city
Marseille today gave jail sentences ranging from two years to 18
months to four neo-Nazi skinhead youths for desecrating a Jewish
cemetery seven years ago, closing a much publicized case of
skinheads in France.
</P>
<P>
The 5th Chamber of the Tribunal of Grand Instance of Marseille
sentenced Olivier Fimbry, 29, and Patrice Laonegro, 31, to two
years in prison, while Yannick Garnier, 27, and Bertrand Nouveau,
29, were given 18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
The four skinheads appeared on court from May 17 to 20 on
charges of "violation of tombs and destruction of mobile objects
or immobile properties belonging to others."
</P>
<P>
Jean-Claude Gos, a fifth skinhead who also led the desecrating
act in the 19th century Jewish cemetery in Carpentras, southern
France, died of a motor accident in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The skinheads destroyed 34 tombs and dug up the body of Felix
Germon, a Jew buried in the cemetery several decades ago, on the
night of May 8, 1990.
</P>
<P>
The barbarous act triggered a strong protest from the Jewish
community in France and drew great public attention.
</P>
<P>
Police, judging from the letters and diaries seized from the
skinheads, found they were systematically motivated by Nazi
ideology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
