<HEADLINE> UN Welcomes Cypriot Adjustment Plan of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations welcomed
today the decision by Cypriot government to adjust the plan
of its joint military exercises with Greece during the ongoing
U.N.-led proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriots
on the island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting here with President
Glafcos Clerides, U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel
said that "I think it's a good step, it shows that there is an
effort being made to create the best possible climate to
facilitate what we are in the process of doing."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government announced Tuesday that Greek warplanes
will suspend flying over Cyprus during the forthcoming joint
military exercises as a good-will gesture for the sake of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed a joint defense pact in November
1993, which provides for joint military exercises between the the
two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has called for good-will gestures by the Greek and
Turkish sides during the ongoing proximity talks, which started
on March 10, in a bid to facilitate the climate for the
face-to-face talks by leaders of the two communities by the
middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Feissel also appealed to the Turkish Cypriot side to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government's unilateral decision to hold flights by
Greek fighters, was also welcomed by Britain, China, France and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and the
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 and the problem has remained
unsolved despite the international community's peace efforts for
the past 23 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
