<HEADLINE> South African Pregnant Women Infected with HIV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- It was estimated by the end of
1996 there were 14.07 percent of South African women attending public
health services' antenatal clinics were infected with HIV, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was based on a sample of 15,044 specimens screened during the
seventh national annual survey in a series of unlinked anonymous
surveys between October and November 1996, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
About 2.4 million, accounting for six percent of all South
Africans, are now HIV positive compared to 1.8 million in 1995,
11 percent of the adult population carried the virus.
</P>
<P>
It was estimatd that 90,000 of the 2.4 million would develop
full-blown Aids during 1997 -- 20,000 of them children, the survey
said.
</P>
<P>
According to an official statistics, HIV infection had increased
among women of all age groups, especially among women aged between
20 and 24.
</P>
<P>
The most alarming feature of the results was a rise in infection
in North West Province where 25 percent of pregnant women were
HIV positive compared with 8.3 perent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The results are of great concern as they indicate that despite
our efforts the HIV epidemic is still on the increase, " SAPA quoted
Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma as saying.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that South Africa had reached a very serious stage
of the epidemic, adding that medical authorities would conduct a
national review of HIV program in June to determine its strengths and
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
"Out of this fundamental review of the program should emerge a
new path in our fight against HIV-Aids," Zuma said. enditem

