<HEADLINE> Various Departments Join in Fight Against Drug-Related Crimes-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Health and the State Pharmaceutical
Administration said they are striving to curb the abuse of
anesthetics and crack down upon unauthorized drug-rehabilitation
medicines.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation has
pledged to set up a system for examining restricted chemicals for
export and import.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP) has issued a circular
demanding procuratorial bodies across the country to issue arrest
warrants on drug charges promptly and according to law.
</P>
<P>
Those who should be indicted on drug charges must be brought to
justice in accordance with the law, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
The police have reported a number of successes in the fight
this month, which is expected to continue through the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
The drug problem was effectively wiped out in China shortly
after the country was liberated by the Chinese Communist Party in
1949. Top officials attributed the victory to the widespread
participation of the public.
</P>
<P>
The country's current drug troubles arose from the opening
policy and the more rampant international narcotics crimes, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Now with anti-drug hotlines opened, all of Chinese society has
been mobilized to join the offensives against narcotics crimes.
</P>
<P>
Head of the NCNC Tao Siju, who is also Public Security
Minister, pledged that with public support, "China's goal of
wiping out the drug problem shall be finally realized." 
