<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Havel Calls for Long-Term Vision in Developing Czech-German Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Vaclav Havel, president of the Czech
Republic, today called on politicians of both Germany and the
Czech Republic to give "long-term common interests priority" to
forge better bilateral relations for the future.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the German parliament in Bonn, Havel
said the German-Czech reconciliation accord should been seen as
"real historical opportunity" for a firm and durable coexistence
of both countries.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by the two governments in January and
approved by the parliaments in February.
</P>
<P>
Havel said the accord had created a "extremely favorable
climate" not only for the development of the bilateral ties, but
also for the cooperation between the two countries at the European
level.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Germany regretted the suffering and injustice
caused to the Czech people under Nazi occupation while Prague
expressed its regret for its expulsion of Sudeten-Germans and the
confiscation of their property after World War II.
</P>
<P>
Some 2.5 million Sudeten-Germans were expelled from territories
they had occupied for centuries in former Czechoslovakia in 1945,
accused by the Czeches of having been traitors who backed Adolf
Hitler's carve-up and occupation of their country from 1938.
</P>
<P>
Sudeten-Germans called their expulsion "one of the biggest
post-war cases of ethnic cleansing."
</P>
<P>
They also protest against the reconciliation accord in which
there was no mention of their right to resettle in the Czech
Republic and no measures for restitution or compensation of
properties seized after the deportations.
</P>
<P>
Havel said his country could not accept the return of
Sudeten-Germans.
</P>
<P>
"Just as Germany today cannot bring back to life tens of
thousands of Czech Nazi victims and turn the clock back to
1938 ... the Czech Republic cannot give back the old homes of the
expelled Germans," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
