<HEADLINE> South African Firm to Set Up Brewery in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South African Breweries Ltd.
(SAB) had decided to establish a modern brewery in Thika town, 40
kilometers northeast of Nairobi, the Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The brewery with a annual capacity of 800,000 hectoliters
will be built at a cost of 45 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 new jobs will be created while the multiplier effect
at supplier and retail level should boost the number of job
opportunities to about 7,000.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted SAB Managing Director Andre Parker
as saying that the current beer consumption levels in Kenya are
less than half what they should be.
</P>
<P>
There exists substantial room for growth through the benefit
of healthy competition, a broader choice of products,
advertising, promotions and improved levels of customer service,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The South African venture will directly challenge Kenya
Breweries which used to enjoy a monopoly before the country's
economy was liberalized.
</P>
<P>
The second half-year results in 1996 of Kenya Breweries showed
that its profit before tax increased by 33 percent to more than
17 million U.S. Dollars compared with the first half of last
year.
</P>
<P>
SAB has already established itself in Sub-Saharan Africa and
currently accounted for more than a half of the beer produced and
sold on the African continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
