<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Purchase Goes Smoothly Across China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's grain departments had
purchased 118.5 billion kg of grain from farmers by the end of
March, hitting the highest yearly grain purchase on record.
</P>
<P>
China reaped a bumper grain harvest last year, with a total
production of 490 billion kg, an increase of 23.5 billion kg over
1995.
</P>
<P>
The country raised the grain purchase price by 42 percent this
year, giving a boost to grain farming, and grain departments at
all levels have taken steps to organize the purchasing.
</P>
<P>
The country's grain reserve has shown a steady increase, with
the total reserves in the northeastern provinces and the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region increasing by almost a half over the
highest reported level.
</P>
<P>
To relieve the pressure on purchasing and storing, as much as
6.25 billion kg of grain produced in the northeastern provinces
and Inner Mongolia have been transported into middle or large
cities and low-yield regions.
</P>
<P>
The prices of most of the grain types have remained stable on
the grain market, except for a slight price drop of some specific
varieties. By the end of March, the grain departments had sold
70.5 billion kg of grain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
