<HEADLINE> Kenya's Hotels to Install Condom Dispensers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- All bars and lodges in Kenya
will soon be required to install condom dispensers in a bid to
prevent HIV/Aids disease, according to a Daily Nation report
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a three-day workshop on HIV/Aids control and
prevention, Tom Okeyo, official of the National Aids and Sexually
Transmitted Diseases Control Program, said the proposed policy had
been approved by Kenyan Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Upon the ratification of the proposal by Kenyan parliament, he
noted, the renewal of licenses for such business would be pegged
on whether they adhered to the requirement.
</P>
<P>
The official told the on-going workshop that the World Bank is
funding 22 HIV/Aids control and prevention projects which will
ensure that any bar or lodge has a condom dispenser.
</P>
<P>
He said, "managing HIV/Aids can be a very simple
matter by treating sexually-transmitted infections and ensuring
that condoms are available to those who need them.
</P>
<P>
Okeyo pointed out that if these two can be achieved, half of
the battle against HIV/Aids disease will have been won, adding
that the pilot project in Nyeri, 150 kilometers northeast
Nairobi, has achieved successful results.
</P>
<P>
Similar efforts in Thailand, Western Europe, North America and
Australia have yielded tremendous results, he said, adding that
the prevalence of HIV/Aids in these regions is on the decline.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 World Population Data Sheet has ranked Kenya among 30
countries whose future population projections will be affected
adversely by the HIV/Aids scourge.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 1.7 million Kenyans who are infected with
the Aids virus in the East African country which has a population
of 28 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
