<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.S.-Japan Summit to Focus on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto will leave for Washington later today for talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton on a wide range of issues including
regional security.
</P>
<P>
In their talks on April 25 in Washington, Hashimoto and Clinton
will give priority to regional security issues such as the
U.S. military presence in Okinawa and security in East Asia,
Japanese government officials said.
</P>
<P>
This is Hashimoto's first visit to the U.S. capital since he
took office in January last year. The Hashimoto-Clinton summit is
the sixth but the first since their reelections late last year.
</P>
<P>
Their talks are also expected to cover Japan's trade surplus
and possible Russian participation in the June summit of the Group
of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations in Denver, Colorado, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
On the Okinawa issue, Hashimoto will likely play up the
"strength and executive power" of his second-term cabinet by
pointing to his success in maintaining the legal use of land in
Okinawa by U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
Japan hurriedly enacted a revised law last Thursday to allow
the continued compulsory leasing of land for use by the
U.S. forces, a move appreciated by Washington.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 landowners, who own a total of about 36,200 square
meters of land on which 12 U.S. military facilities are stationed,
have refused to renew leases that expire on May 14. Without the
revised law, the continued use of the land by U.S. forces would be
illegal after the date.
</P>
<P>
With the passage of the revised law, described by observers as
Hashimoto's "big present" for the summit, U.S. troops in Okinawa
can legally use the land even after the expiry of the leases.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa, which accounts for only 0.6 percent of Japan's total
land, is home to 75 percent of the total land leased by the
U.S. military in the country. More than half of the 47,000
U.S. troops in Japan are stationed in the island prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Discontent among Okinawans over the U.S. military presence has
been rising following a series of assaulting incidents on Japanese
women by U.S. servicemen.
</P>
<P>
While refraining from asking for a cut in the number of
U.S. troops in Japan's southernmost island, Hashimoto is likely to
ask Clinton for more cooperation in alleviating the burden of
people in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Hashimoto and Clinton are expected to
confirm that the U.S. will maintain its current 100,000 military
personnel in the East Asia-Pacific region, as repeatedly stressed
by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Vice President Al
Gore and Secretary of Defense William Cohen in recent visits to
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to confirm the bilateral security
alliance, including their initiative to conclude a review of the
1978 Guidelines for Japan-U.S. Defense Cooperation by the fall.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is likely to express his intention of extending the
range of Japan-U.S. defense cooperation to the whole Asia-Pacific
region as he mentioned recently in a meeting with some leaders of
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told the LDP group that while reviewing the 1978
Guidelines for Japan-U.S. Defense Cooperation, Japan should
consider emergencies not only in the Korean Peninsula, but also in
China's Taiwan and the Nansha Islands, reflecting Japan's
ambitions to interfere in other countries' affairs.
</P>
<P>
Washington is likely to urge Tokyo to step up its efforts
toward domestic demand-led economic growth via deregulation to
contain Japan's trade surplus in automobile and other exports to
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, Japan's trade surplus with the U.S. jumped
11.2 percent over the previous year to 379.83 billion yen (3
billion U.S. dollars) amid strong exports of automobile and office
equipment.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have warned Japan against a resurgence of a
trade surplus amid the yen's recent sharp drop against the dollar,
while expressing concerns over Japan's tightening of fiscal
spending and the consumption tax hike as leading to draining
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Another issue may come up in the summit is a U.S. initiative
seeking a new bilateral framework for discussing sector-by-sector
progress in deregulation to provide greater foreign access to
Japan's markets.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory talks for the June G-7 summit in Danver and the
reforms of the United Nations will also be on the agenda of the
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
