<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vitamin C May Help Ease Angina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Vitamin C appears to help ease
angina pectoris and in turn prevent its resulting sudden pains in
the chest, a German cardiovascular expert said today.
</P>
<P>
Eberhard Bassenge, of the University of Freiburg, told an
annual conference of the German Society of Cardiologists that the
vitamin could keep conventional pain-killer potent against angina.
</P>
<P>
Many pain-killers become less effective after frequent use to
fight angina, Bassenge noted, adding that his research, however,
shows that vitamin C intake helps prevent this loss of effect.
</P>
<P>
Angina pectoris, which triggers sudden sharp pains in the
chest, is known to be the result of block of blood supply to the
heart due to the narrowing of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
Bassenge, a professor at the German university, added that
vitamin C may also prevent the tendency for blood platelets to
coagulate and thus block blood vessels to the heart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
