<HEADLINE> Local PC Maker Signs Big Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing-based Legend Computer
Group, one of the major domestic PC makers, signed a
110-million-US dollar-worth export deal at the on-going 81st China
Export Commodities Fair held here.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed between Legend and US-based
Source One Enterprises, Legend will ship 105,000 branded personal
computers to North America over two years.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts considered the deal a breakthrough for China's
domestic PC industry, marking the entrance of Chinese PC makers in
the competitive international market.
</P>
<P>
Legend is China's top PC maker. The group posted sales of
215,000 PCs with a volume of 7.74 billion yuan last year. The
group took a lead in the market share by grabbing 10 percent of
the total, surpassing such big names as IBM, Compaq and HP.
</P>
<P>
According to Zeng Maochao, chairman of Legend, the group in the
past decade turned out China's first batch of computers based on
the 486, Pentium, and Pentium Pro chips. The group also registered
double growth for three years straight since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Zeng hoped his group can develop into a large information
industry enterprise competitive in the global market in the next
ten years.
</P>
<P>
Legend pocketed its first export order worth 22 million US
dollars at the previous fair.
</P>
<P>
Also at this fair, Duan Yongji, president of Stone Corporation,
another non-governmental high-tech enterprise, indicated that the
big players in the computer market have shifted the manufacture to
developing countries, including China, in a bid to reduce the
cost. His company has clinched 21 joint ventures with foreign
partners for keeping abreast with the international level.
</P>
<P>
What Stone will focus on in the coming years is developing
software products, he said, adding that major computer
corporations, including IBM, HP, and AST have selected Stone's
Chinese-based software as the standard Chinese environment and
agreed to pre-install the software in their PC products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
