<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Considering to Join Hague Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China is considering joining the
"Convention for the Protection of Cultural Property in the event
of Armed Conflict," also known as the "Hague Convention,"
Deputy-director of the State Bureau of Cultural Relics Ma Zishu
said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are conducting studies on joining the convention," Ma
said. "But we have to consult the ministries of Foreign Affairs,
Civil Affairs and National Defense before we apply."
</P>
<P>
Visiting officials of the United Nation's Education, Science
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) today outlined for Ma the
conventions on international cultural relics protection.
</P>
<P>
Some 89 countries have joined the Hague Convention, which is
one of the three conventions on international cultural heritage
protection, approved by the member countries of UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
They have all promised to protect the cultural properties both
at home and in enemy states during wartime. The cultural
properties under the protection of the convention, which took
effect in 1954, are marked with a shield-shaped pattern in blue
and white.
</P>
<P>
China is a member country of another two conventions, the
"Convention on the Means of Prohibiting and Preventing the Illicit
Import, Export and Transfer of Ownership of Cultural Property"
(1970), and the convention on returning the stolen or illegally
Exported Cultural Property (1985), which it also helped to draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
