<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Maps out New Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South China's Shenzhen city, the
first special economic zone in the country, plans to register an
economic growth rate of 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan set recently, the city plans to produce a
gross domestic product of 112 billion yuan for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Other planned economic targets for this year include a 16
percent increase of fixed assets investment, a 3.3 percent
increase of foreign trade, and a 16.9 percent increase of retail
sales of social commodities.
</P>
<P>
The present comprehensive economic strength of the city ranks
the top fifth of the country's large and medium-sized
cities. Shenzhen's foreign trade volume ranks No.1 among these
cities.
</P>
<P>
The economic development has entered a period of stable
development, said a high-ranking local official.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to use 1.8 billion US dollars of foreign funds
this year, 25 percent less than in last year, said the official,
noting that last year's downward trend of the sum of foreign funds
inflow will have a negative impact on this year.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the city will try to attract more loans from
foreign governments or international financial organizations,
rather than making direct foreign investments the priority.
</P>
