<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Industries Asked to Treat Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Environment (DOE)
of Bangladesh has directed the industries concerned to set up
waste treatment plants to treat the solid and chemical waste they
release, DOE officials said.
</P>
<P>
The DOE has identified 1,167 industrial units as heavy
polluters and served notices on them for taking effective measures
to control environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the department said about 14,000 tons of
solid waste and 16,000 cubic meters of chemical waste are
discharged by the industries every year into the rivers in the
capital Dhaka and its adjacent areas.
</P>
<P>
It also said more than 1,200 factories in the country discharge
about 35,000 cubic meters of waste into rivers everyday.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey report, major polluters include
fertilizer, pulp and paper, dyeing, textile and iron and steel
industries.
</P>
<P>
The industries, set up without proper planning and waste
treatment plants, have produced many environmentally harmful
effects by releasing toxic chemicals, solid waste and effluents,
the report said. It added that many such industries were built
near the banks of rivers for quick disposal of waste.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
