<HEADLINE> AL Chief Urges UN to Condemn Israel on Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdul-Meguid said today that he expected the U.N. General
Assembly to pass a resolution today banning the Israeli building
activities on occupied Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid, who flew to Paris Wednesday for talks on the
stalled Mideast peace process with French officials, made the
statement in an interview over telephone with the Egyptian Voice
of Arab radio.
</P>
<P>
"Resolutions passed by the world community have their
political weight because they stress Israel's isolation and the
extent of its non-compliance with the international law," he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the European mediation in the peace process as
complementing the U.S. role, he noted that his talks with French
top officials focused on obstacles hindering the peace march, as
well as the French and European efforts in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly will hold an emergency session later
today to discuss Israel's settlement activities in Arab East
Jerusalem and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision last month to build 6,500 Jewish homes in
disputed East Jerusalem has stalled the peace talks and sparked
violence in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Arab group in the U.N. has been seeking a majority of the
185-member General Assembly to stage the special session since
the U.S. last month vetoed two U.N. Security Council resolutions
criticizing Israel on the settlement issue.
</P>
<P>
In Damascus, Syria, three state-run newspapers today also
urged the U.N. General Assembly to impose swift sanctions against
Israel to stop it from building new settlements on Arab lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
