<HEADLINE> China Has Flying Start at Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion
China jumped to a flying start with a 3-0 victory over Australia
at the the women's team competition in the 44th World Table Tennis
Championships which began here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese squad, bidding for its 12th team title, benched
world No. 1 Deng Yaping and sent three youngsters to the court.
</P>
<P>
Yang Ying, Li Ju and Wang Nan, all ranked among the world top
10, beat Australians Shirley Zhou, Yvonne Li and Tammy Gough in
straight sets.
</P>
<P>
China is to take on Russia late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea, who had skipped
previous two world championships, also scored an easy win, beating
Chinese Taipei 3-0.
</P>
<P>
Wi Bok Sun, who hasn't got a world ranking, upset world No. 44
Xu Jing to put the DPR Korea into lead and Kim Hyon Hui, who had
reached the quarter-finals in the Atlanta Olympic Games last
summer, got her team further ahead with a straight set triumph
over Tsui Hsiu-Li.
</P>
<P>
Tu Jong Sil wrapped up the victory after beating Chew Chiu-Tan
in two sets. 
