<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesian Gov't Determined to Hold Smooth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
taken many effective measures, including allocation of a huge fund
and deployment of heavy troops in all important areas, to
maintain security and order for holding a smooth general election
scheduled for May 29.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the three government-recognized contestants --
the ruling party Golkar, the United Development Party (PPP) and
the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) in Jakarta received an
additional 250 million rupiah (one US dollar equals 2,340 rupiah)
each in campaign funds from the city budget.
</P>
<P>
Reports said other provincial administrations have also
provided additional funds to the parties, which had earlier
received 500 million rupiah each from the central government.
</P>
<P>
While no official figures are available on how much money will
be used for security purpose, Finance Minister Mar'ie Huhamad said
no less than 90 million US dollars has been earmarked for the
election which is held every five years.
</P>
<P>
A Jakarta daily, however, quoting an unnamed police source
saying that 8 billion rupiah has been set aside for security
purposes.
</P>
<P>
This means that each of Indonesia's 27 provinces will get an
average of 10 million rupiah every day throughout the campaign
period which starts on April 27 and winds up on May 23.
</P>
<P>
This year's general election is Indonesia's seventh since it
gained independence in 1945 and the sixth since the new order
administration under President Soeharto rose to power.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that judging from the country's history of
having a high participation rate in general elections, most of the
120 million eligible voters are likely to flock to the 305,508
polling booths across the archipelago this year.
</P>
<P>
The three political parties vie for 425 of the 500 seats of the
House of Representatives (DPR) in the forthcoming election. The
remaining 75 seats are reserved for the Indonesian armed forces
whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
Aside from deploying security personnel, mainly from the
national police, with the support of the army, navy, air force and
civilian defense units, the government has also formulated a new
set of regulations preventing supporters of Golkar, PPP and PDI
from clashing.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Indonesian Police Information Service Brig. Gen.
Nurfaizi has said recently that security maintenance for the 1997
general election will cover three periods.
</P>
<P>
"The first is what we call the pre-event period, the second is
the May 29 general election, and the third is the post-event
period which will last until the 1998 General Assembly of the
People's Deliberative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest
legislative body," he said.
</P>
<P>
For the pre-event period, the police will deploy 19,000
policemen, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
"However, on the 'peak day' of May 29, no less than 126,000
policemen will be fielded," he said, adding that the figure
constitutes more than two-thirds of the country's police force."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the army, navy and air force along with civilian
defense units have declared their readiness to ensure that the
general election will proceed smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The government has also asked the three political parties to
set up their own security forces which will work in coordination
with the police and the military.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the financial and security preparations, analysts
said the government looks set to have a smooth and orderly general
election.
</P>
<P>
After all, they added, President Soeharto himself has said that
a general election which is free from any obstacle, disturbance
and threat from any body for any reason is a must.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
