<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK MTR Platforms To Get Screen Doors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Mass Transit
Railway Corporation (MTRC) has decided to install platform screen
doors on all its 28 underground stations, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after years of deliberation and a feasibility
study involving a pilot test at Choi Hung station, MTRC operations
director Bill Donald said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The screen doors will stop accidents, especially on overcrowded
platforms, and suicides by cutting off access to the railway
tracks.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, much of the 35 million HK dollars (4.5
million US dollars) the MTRC spends annually on electricity at its
stations will be saved because the screen doors will prevent
air-conditioning from being lost in the tunnels.
</P>
<P>
The scheme is estimated to cost one billion HK dollars (128
million US dollars), with work expected to begin within the next
two years, Donald said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the MTRC's new signaling system had already taken
into account the possibility of screen doors being installed.
</P>
<P>
Under the new signaling system, train-stopping positions would
be adapted to achieve the accuracy needed to operate the doors.
</P>
<P>
The MTRC's 10 above-ground stations are not included in the
project because their platforms are not air-conditioned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
