<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Accounting Society to Remain Independent After July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Society of
Accountants will remain independent after China resumes the
exercise of power over Hong Kong on July 1, a Chinese government
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
As a civil organization of accountants, the Hong Kong Society
of Accountants will continue to be independent after July 1, Ding
Pingzhun, Secretary General of the Chinese Institute of Certified
Public Accountants, said at a news briefing prior to an
international seminar on China's economic reform and the opening
of its accountancy market.
</P>
<P>
Ding said that the friendly cooperation between the Chinese
Institute and the Hong Kong Society has contributed greatly to the
economic and trade relations between China's inland areas and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to the motherland, the Chinese
Institute and the Hong Kong Society do not subordinate to each
other and will not interfere with each other, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The relations between the Institute and the Society will be
like two brothers," he told journalists.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar will be attended by nearly 500 accounting
officials and experts from China and a number of other countries
and regions in the Asia-Pacific area, according to the
co-sponsors, the Institute and the Society. 
</P>
