<HEADLINE> More Efforts to Improve Creativity of Youngsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Experts said the current
education system must be improved to help develop the creativity
of youngsters, as the latest survey suggests that the system has
hindered students' creativity.
</P>
<P>
The China University of Political Science and Law began to
conduct the survey on the training of youngsters' creativity in
May, 1996, among 2,000 students in ten universities and colleges
and ten high schools.
</P>
<P>
Three quarters of the respondents think that the education of
middle and primary schools aims at enabling students to enter
universities, while 53 percent agree that "the education methods
conflict with the cultivation of creativity", according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
This shows the current examination-oriented education system is
not favorable for the development of the youngsters' creativity,
said Ma Kangmei, head of the advising group of the survey and
vice-president of the China University of Political Science and
Law.
</P>
<P>
She said that only 42 percent of the students attach importance
to the book and other tools, provided by their families and
schools for development of creativity, but 78 percent of them
agreed that "in their teachers' eyes, a good student should be
obedient and always listen to the teachers."
</P>
<P>
This showed that under the traditional influence, schools,
families, and society do not pay much attention to the cultivation
of students' creativity, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that the survey also discovered that the text books
are outdated and have lost contact with the reality and that the
student's knowledge structure is irrational. For example, 38
percent of the students said the knowledge they acquired at school
can only fetter the development of their creativity.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 20 percent of the junior middle school
students, 30 percent of the senior middle school students and half
of the college students think that their teachers give lessons
through "cramming", which indicates that teachers and parents
should improve themselves to provide better education.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the simplistic teaching style and
the lack of funds in both school and family education hindered the
development of the youngsters' creativity.
</P>
<P>
"Creativity should be the prime theme of the education," said
Zhang Kaixun, a member of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference and the China
Inventors' Association. He added that the students can only
succeed in their future careers by learning to use the knowledge
creatively.
</P>
<P>
Experts urged that to cultivate the students' creativity, the
examination-oriented education system should be reformed, the text
books be updated and the teachers and parents be trained to
improve their educational concepts, knowledge structure, and
education methods.
</P>
<P>
They also called on the youngsters to study the Intellectual
Property Protection Law, and grow up to be creative, talented people
with a good legal awareness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
