<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Court Insolvency Cases Up 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of new court
insolvencies in Hong Kong hit 1,119 in 1996-97, up 10 percent
against the previous year, the Official Receiver, Robin Hearder,
revealed today.
</P>
<P>
But the figure was still low in comparison with overseas
jurisdictions in view of the huge volume of economic activities in
Hong Kong, Hearder said when reviewing the work of the Official
Receiver's Office in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
There were 557 new compulsory company liquidations in the year,
accounting for less than one percent of the total number of new
companies incorporated in the year, or around 0.1 percent of the
total number of companies in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A decline in business, cash flow problems and poor management
were among the major causes of failure.
</P>
<P>
New bankruptcies totaled 562 during 1996-97, the first year
since 1988-89 with the number of new bankruptcies exceeding that
of new compulsory company liquidations.
</P>
<P>
Inability to meet liabilities arising from personal guarantees,
a decline in business and excessive use of personal credit
facilities bore the blame for the bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
Sectors affected by compulsory company liquidations and
bankruptcies included garment and knitting manufacturing,
importers and exporters, restaurants and canteens, electrical and
electronic manufacturing, construction and engineering, land and
property development and investment, as well as plastic products
manufacturing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
