<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Efforts to Save Mideast peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today described Egypt's hard-earned peace with Israel as a model
for Arabs and called for efforts to save the Mideast process from
total collapse.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the remarks in an address to the nation on the
occasion of the 15th anniversary of liberation of Egypt's Sinai
Peninsula from the 15-year Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
"Such a just peace would re-arrange relations among peoples in
the region on new bases that guarantee good neighborly ties,
balanced interests and would also achieve security for all
parties," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Peace between Egypt and Israel is a true model of balanced
peace that managed to weather fierce storms as it was based on
balanced rights and interests."
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to make peace with Israel in
1979 and a key mediator in the peace process. But ties between
the two countries have been cool. Tensions are mounting since
Israel began last month to build 6,500 Jewish homes in disputed
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak warned that the peace process is facing a severe and
critical test after having taken long strides ahead.
</P>
<P>
"I feared that the present violence in the occupied territories
would escalate into a dangerous extent as a result of continued
settlement policy," he added.
</P>
<P>
But the president said he is confident that the majority of
Palestinians and Israelis still wish to pursue the peace march and
hope for a peaceful co-existence that would erase the "remnants of
fear, hate and mutual mistrust."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called on the Palestinians to overcome "feelings of
frustration and despair" and remain confident that just peace
would triumph despite all difficulties and ambitions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged Israel to realize that security comes only
with mutual recognition between the different parties, otherwise,
nothing else could compensate for peace.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Mubarak called on peace advocates in the whole
world to back the Arab efforts for the sake of salvaging the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also urged peace march partners to exert their utmost in
order to contain the peril before damage escalates, warning that
the alternative would be "dangerous and fearsome." 
</P>
</TEXT>
