<HEADLINE> SA's Arms Sale to Uganda No Harmful to Peace: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's National
Conventional Arms Control Committee Chairman Kader Asmal has
admitted that his country is supplying arms to Uganda, which is
alleged to be the main supporters of Zairean rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
The sale of "modest amount of arms to Uganda for defense
purposes" was "perfectly legal" and South Africa had a guarantee
from Uganda that the weapons would not be rechanneled to the
rebels in Zaire, today's Business Day quoted Asmal as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asmal said the arms sale would not have an impact on the South
Africa-broked peace talks aimed at resolving the crisis in the
Great Lake region between Zairean President Mobuto Sese Seko and
Laurent Kabila, the leader of Zairean rebels.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was exporting only small and limited amounts, not
truckloads of arms and "I don't see its relevance to the peace
talks," Asmal stressed.
</P>
<P>
South African Defense Minister Joe Modise also said Uganda had
advised that it had complied with the end-user certificates with
regard to the arms and equipment supplied by South Africa.
</P>
<P>
All exports of arms required an end-user certificate which was
internationally recognized "undertaking by the government of the
recipient country that the items purchased were for its sole use and
not destined for transfer or re-export", Modise said. enditem

