<HEADLINE> 34 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-four rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in operations
launched by the Turkish security forces in southeastern Turkey,
according to an official statement today.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the office of the Emergency Regional
Rule said that in the past 24-hour-long operations to clear the
PKK militants from the region, the Turkish security forces
killed 21 PKK members, including four women, on Incebel mountain
in Hani town of Diyarbakir, center of southeastern Turkey, eight
in Gulyazi area in Sirnak province bordering northern Iraq and
five in Hozat and Pertek towns of Tunceli province.
</P>
<P>
One soldier of the Turkish security forces also died in the
armed clashes with the PKK guerrillas in the region, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Over 21,000 people, including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops, have been killed in conflicts since August
1984 when the PKK started a separatist war in the east and the
southeast of Turkey for autonomy. 
</P>
