<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Rising Crime Boosts Private Security Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Private security services are
booming in Germany as a result of the rising crime and inadequate
police forces, and their total business volume doubled over 1991
to about 5 billion marks (about 3 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As factors that have boosted Germany's private security sector,
which now employs 112,000 people, said German press reports today,
more German companies are hiring outside security guards and
insurance companies' security provisions are increasingly strict.
</P>
<P>
Between 1985 and 1995, while crime cases nearly doubled to 6.7
million, police officers increased by one quarter to 280,000.
Nearly 40 percent of Germans in a recent survey regarded domestic
security as the country's biggest political problem at present.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also showed that theft alone causes 4 billion marks
(2.4 billion dollars) loss to retail businesses each year. And the
damage caused by industrial espionage is estimated to amount to 20
billion marks (12 billion dollars), said the reports.
</P>
<P>
Germany's private security firms carry out security checks at
nine German airports and offer detective services. They also guard
factories, cash transports, military facilities, homes for asylum
seekers, nuclear power plants, and underground trains and stations.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports criticizing the martial-style behavior
of private security guards at underground stations, the
recruitment of rightists as well as bungled operations, which have
affected the image of the sector.
</P>
<P>
Pay in the sector runs relatively low, ranging from 8.70 marks
(5.22 dollars) an hour for a security guard in the country's
eastern state of Thuringia to at least 15 marks (9.0 dollars) in
the western state of North Rhine Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of all security guards in Germany are workers,
the reports said. Government regulations as of April 1996 require
newcomers in the security sector to have a training course of 40
hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0107 </DOCNO>
