<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Ethnic Region to Become Large Fertilizer Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China has designated its
northwest Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region to be one of the key
areas to develop the chemical industry, turning the region into a
major nitrogenous fertilizer production base in China, according
to sources from the Ministry of Chemical Industry (MCI).
</P>
<P>
Six large fertilizer production facilities with a combined
capacity of 1.2 million tons of synthetic ammonia have been or
will be underway in the region, said an official with the MCI.
</P>
<P>
The projects are to use Xinjiang's rich natural gas resources
as the raw material, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Urumqi Petrochemical Plant has almost finalized the
construction of a facility with a production capacity of 300,000
tons of synthetic ammonia. The first batch of carbamide is
expected to be turned out from the plant next month.
</P>
<P>
A similar facility with a capacity of 100,000 tons at the
Xinjiang Chemical Fertilizer Plant is set to finish construction
within the year.
</P>
<P>
Another four facilities funded by the state, two
300,000-tonnage plants in Korla, one the same size in Kuqa and one
200,000-tonnage plant in Zepu, are doing feasibility studies on
localization of equipment or evaluating investments and the
environmental impact.
</P>
<P>
Gu Xiulian, Chinese minister of Chemical Industry, revealed in
a recent national conference on chemical construction that the
country planned to build 470 large- and medium-sized chemical
projects with a total investment of 260 billion yuan. Agro-related
projects, in particular chemical fertilizer and pesticide
production, will be given priority, she said. 
</P>
