<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Vows Yield to U.S. Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar today reiterated its
policies, aims and objectives already laid down, saying, "There is
no reason to deviate from its original path to serve the interests
of a foreign government."
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions imposed by the United States on Myanmar, we
believe, are for their own domestic political consumption," said
an official statement released here today.
</P>
<P>
"Myanmar has opened its doors to outside investments and its
abundant natural resources will benefit all those who come to
invest," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"But if the United States refuses to come in to invest or pull
its companies out of doing business in Myanmar, we can only feel
sorry for the U.S. companies, because they will not get a second
chance later to invest in Myanmar if opportunities are taken over
by companies from nations with consistent foreign policies," the
statement warned.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government announced its decision on Tuesday to ban
new U.S. investment in Myanmar. However, the ban is reported not
to affect existing U.S. investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The United States halted direct financial assistance and
blocked much international aid to Myanmar since the Myanmar State
Law and Order Restoration Council took over state power in 1988.
It has also barred the entry of certain Myanmar officials into the
country since last October.
</P>
<P>
Of the total foreign investment of over 6 billion U.S. dollars
in Myanmar by the end of March this year, the United States ranks
fourth with 582 million dollars in 16 projects after Britain,
Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Major U.S. investment in Myanmar involves UNOCAL and TEXACO oil
 companies' natural gas development at two Myanmar offshore gas
fields, the Yadana and the Yetagun.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
