<HEADLINE> Japan Puts Diplomatic Missions on Alert After Peru Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan has put all its diplomatic
missions abroad on high alert against possible revenge attacks
after Tuesday's violent end to the hostage crisis at the Japanese
ambassador's residence in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Japan has especially tightened security at the Japanese Embassy
in Peru, Foreign Ministry spokesman Hiroshi Hashimoto said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama
said that his country needs to establish a crisis management
system to deal with terrorist attacks outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama added that the government would consider dispatching
special commando forces when overseas terrorist incidents occur.
</P>
<P>
The recent 127-day-old hostage crisis ended when Peruvian
forces stormed the Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima,
rescuing 71 of the 72 hostages, including 24 Japanese nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, the hostage-taker, had
vowed to launch avenge attacks in response to the killing of its
14 members in the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
