<HEADLINE> Drug Worth 9 M U.S. Dollars Seized in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The South African Narcotics
Bureau (SANAB) has seized drugs worth 40 million Rand (about nine
million U.S. Dollars) at the Johannesburg International Airport
in the past 16 months, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Between January 1, 1996 to April 22, the SANAB Unit at the
airport seized 131,424 grams of cocaine, 79,126 grams of dagga,
29 LSD units and 6,000 Mandrax tablets, leading to 54
prosecutions, said the source.
</P>
<P>
From January 1, 1994 to March this year, cocaine worth about
18 million U.S. Dollars were confiscated at the airport, it
added.
</P>
<P>
"These figures show that the police are not sitting on their
hands in their fight against domestic and international drug
trafficking," North Rand police spokesman Superintendent Eugene
Opperman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SANAB Unit on the North and East Rand also
confiscated 124 grams of cocaine, 250,772 Mandrax tablets, 5,070
kilograms of dagga, 385 units of LSD and 193 Ecstasy tablets from
January 1, 1996 to April 22, leading to 434 prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
SANAB seized three kilograms of cocaine on April 21 at the
airport with one person arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
