<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops Sent to Ease Crisis in Nigeria's Oil Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The oil city of Warri in southern
Nigeria witnessed calm on Wednesday for the first time in a month
following the deployment of troops to put in check the orgy of
violence there, according to press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Violence broke out between the Itsekiri and Ijaw tribes on
March 24 following the relocation of the headquarters of the
Warri South Local Government from where Ijaws live to an
Itsekiri-inhabited area.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 people died in the communal clashes with property
worth millions of Naira damaged.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier sent Naval personnel and gunship to
help the police to restore peace there. But the Naval presence
was minimal and the situation seemed to be beyond the police.
</P>
<P>
"There is a constitutional role for the Army. It is to help
the police maintain law and order in the country. If the
situation is beyond the police, the Army can go there to help,"
said Col. Godwin Ugbo, the acting director of defence
information.
</P>
<P>
He declined to comment on the strength of the troops deployed
to the area.
</P>
<P>
In Abuja, the Nigerian capital, Petroleum Resources Minister
Chief Dan Etete warned on Wednesday that the government would no
longer tolerate situations in which host communities hold oil
companies to ransome to register their protest.
</P>
<P>
He said the community leaders in such areas owed it a duty to
restrain their youths from taking out their disputes on oil
installations.
</P>
<P>
In the early stage of the crisis, the Ijaw people held hostage
127 oil workers of Shell Petroleum Development Company and 50 oil
traders in order to arouse government attention to their protest
against the relocation of local government.
</P>
<P>
Some of the production facilities of Shell and Chevron have
been damaged, forcing a cut down in their crude oil production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Exports Increase in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Earnings from gold exports in
Uganda has increased by 72 percent from 35.15 million U.S.
Dollars in the 1995/96 financial year to 60.32 million Dollars
from the second half of 1996 to date.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bank of Uganda today, Uganda's earnings from
gold exports had increased from less than one million Dollars in
1993/94 financial year to 12.44 million Dollars in 1994/95
financial year.
</P>
<P>
The increase was attributed by an official of the bank to some
gold leakages into Uganda from neighboring Zaire, where trading
in minerals has been disrupted by civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
