<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auctioning Off South China Province's Largest Loss-Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Haikou Textile and Dye Mill,
the largest failing state-owned enterprises in south China's
island province of Hainan, has decided to auction off its assets
to pay for its debts.
</P>
<P>
The mill has 68 million yuan in registered capital, and has
1,728 employees including 34 retired people on its payroll.
</P>
<P>
The mill has been running a deficit ever since it was set up in
1986, because of chaotic management practices. It declared
bankruptcy in December of last year, with total assets of 213
million yuan, and a debt burden reaching 362 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The mill will be auctioned off at a base price of 130 million
yuan on the 8th of next month. All transactions are to be handled
with one payment and within 15 days, China Business Times reports.
</P>
<P>
The mill's employees have two options: one is to collect
three-years' salary in one lump sum and to look for a job by
themselves, the other is to accept training and possible
re-employment arrangements from the government.
</P>
<P>
The mill's losses account for nearly half of the total amount
of losses of the state-owned industrial enterprises in Haikou, the
province's capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
