<HEADLINE> Pak PM Vows to Improve Health Facilities for Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif vowed here today to take concrete measures to improve
health facilities for children in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government is giving top priority to the health sector and
a network of children's' hospitals would be established all over
the country, Nawaz said while addressing the first-ever
international pediatric nursing conference being held here.
</P>
<P>
"Health is a basic requirement of every citizen, it is second
name for life," he said.
</P>
<P>
A healthy society generates healthy minds among the new
generation who has to shoulder national responsibilities in the
future, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed deep anguish and concern over the
infant mortality rate where 10 percent of children die before
their fifth birthday and 48 percent suffer from various diseases
and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite paucity of funds and meager resources his
government is striving hard to improve health standards for
children.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to extend health care facilities to children at
their doorsteps and at their educational institutions because we
believe in establishing an unprecedented health infrastructure for
them," he said.  
</P>
