<HEADLINE> Uganda Currency Depreciates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda Shilling depreciated
by 2.4 percent last week, reported the local mass media here
today.
</P>
<P>
The week average inter-bank mid-rate declined to 1,050
Shillings against one U.S. Dollar from 1,025 Shillings for one
Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation is due to a slump in coffee exports, analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
Public relations manager of Uganda Commercial Bank Dan
Nsibambi was quoted as saying that the change in the money market
was expected since the season of coffee -- the country's leading
foreign exchange earner was coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
A manager at Musicraft Foreign Exchange Bureau was quoted as
warning of a possible rise in commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the Bank of Uganda (central bank of the eastern
African country) intervenes to stabilize the foreign exchange
rates, they will continue rising," he predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
