<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Equality Among All Nationalities Ensures Stability in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Political equality among all
nationalities has ensured social stability and encouraged economic
development in Inner Mongolia, one of China's five autonomous
regions.
</P>
<P>
Ulgi, Chairman of the People's Government of Inner Mongolia,
said the gross domestic product (GDP) in his region reached 98.3
billion yuan (some 12 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, and the
region's economic growth increased by 12.4 percent, higher than
China's average figure.
</P>
<P>
The annual net income of farmers and herdsmen came to 1,602
yuan (200 dollars) in 1996, registering a 23.2 percent increase
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the achievements to the political equality among
all nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that Inner Mongolia registered 169,700
officials of China's ethnic minority groups, accounting for 23.43
of the region's total.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia, occupying a land space of 1.18 million square
kilometers, has a population of 23 million, 3.78 million of which
are Mongolians.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region was established in May 1, 1947, Ulgi
said, adding that this was the Chinese Communist Party's "first
experience" in implementing its autonomous policy in ethnic
minority areas.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the regional commission of
nationalities affairs, the leading officials in towns of minority
nationalities are chosen from ethnic minority groups; in counties
of Han nationality, the head officials are usually Han.
</P>
<P>
For example, though the Oroqen Autonomous Banner, or Alihe
Town, only has an Oroqen population of more than 2,000, the
leading officials there are from the Oroqen nationality.
</P>
<P>
It is also the case in four other Chinese autonomous regions,
namely the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Tibet
Autonomous Region, an official with the State Nationalities
Affairs Commission said.
</P>
<P>
An official with the region's Education Bureau said his region
has also been attentive to the development of the languages of the
minority nationalities.
</P>
<P>
He said the classes taught in Mongolian are very popular in
primary schools and universities in his region, and preferential
policies have been adopted covering ethnic people's university
enrollment, employment and promotion.
</P>
<P>
The region has also adopted a law stipulating that the official
documents and units' signs must be written in both Mongolian and
Han characters.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he added, the region also urged Han officials
in minority areas to study the Mongolian language, and those who
master it will receive an award from the regional government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
