<HEADLINE> Bumper Year for S.African Wine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is expected to have
another bumper wine-producing year in 1997, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
The KWV, leading wine co-operative of the country, said on Wednesday
that South African wine sales are currently booming in Britain and
other European markets.
</P>
<P>
"Indications are that the crop could be another 984 million litres.
This will be approximately three percent smaller than last year's
record crop," said KWV Chairman Lourens Jonker at the company's annual
general meeting in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Jonker said the 1997 crop would be the third largest in history.
</P>
<P>
According to KWV's annual report released earlier this month, the
company's export volumes rose by 35 percent to 11.1 million cases in
1996, compared to 8.2 million cases in 1995.
</P>
<P>
While in value, the company earned the country 550 million Rand
(about 125 million US Dollar) in 1996, almost a 50 percent rise
compared to that in 1995.
</P>
<P>
KWV said South African wine was being exported to about 60
countries worldwide, with the European Union being the biggest
single foreign consumer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, domestic demand for good quality wine has also grown
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Increased tourism, a wider range of wines on offer and higher
disposable income among Black consumers all contribued to increase
sales, said the source. enditem

