<HEADLINE> Zambia's Capital Leases Parks to Non-Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Lusaka City Council (LCC) has
decided to lease the play parks in the capital city of Zambia to
non-profitable organizations to protect their botanical beauty
from commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
The LCC made the decision recently because it is unable to
maintain the parks.
</P>
<P>
Non-profit-making groups have expressed their interest in 80
percent of Lusaka's some 30 play parks.
</P>
<P>
The leased parks should be developed within six months or the
LCC will repossess them.
</P>
<P>
The organizations have to ensure that the parks will not pose
danger to children and there will not be any sanitary danger or
hazardous situation for children.
</P>
<P>
Madras Play Park, which was initially a garbage disposal site,
now has amusement facilities through a project starting two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
The funds for project were raised in the community through
contribution. 
</P>
