<HEADLINE> Dwarf Maize Produces High Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese agronomists are
introducing a dwarf maize into farming production. The new strains
have shown per-unit output increases of 15-30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new corn have been planted on a trial basis on nearly
423,000 ha of farmland in north, northeast, and northwest China
over the past few years, and added a total maize output of 950
million kg.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Youzhi, a senior agronomist of the Agricultural Bureau of
Zhangjiakou City in north China's Hebei Province, began his
research on dwarf maize in the 1960s, and succeeded in cultivating
the first new strain in 1988, experimental planting of which
proved encouraging.
</P>
<P>
The new strain was planted on some 20,000 ha in the suburbs of
the city last year, and had an average per-hectare output of
12,750 kg.
</P>
<P>
The new strain, 70-100 cm lower than traditional maize strains,
is fit for close planting. More farmers have begun to accept
dwarf maize and expect high yields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
