<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Five-Nation Accord on Border Arms Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of China, Russia,
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan signed an agreement on
reduction of military forces in border areas in the Kremlin today,
which is the first of its kind in the Asia Pacific region and also
a result of over seven years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Talks on the accord initially began between China and the
former Soviet Union in November 1989, in line with the agreement
reached by the then top leaders of the two countries on the issue.
</P>
<P>
In April 1990, the Governments of China and the former Soviet
Union signed an agreement on guiding principles of reduction of
military forces and confidence building in the military field in
border areas.
</P>
<P>
After the former Soviet Union broke up and the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) was formed, the talks resumed in 1992
between China and the four CIS members -- Russia, Kazakhstan,
Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
On April 26, 1996, the presidents of China, Russia, Kazakhstan,
Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan signed an agreement on confidence
building in the military field in border areas in Shanghai, China.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the parties further reached consensus on
details of the agreement on reduction of military forces in border
areas, which was inked by the presidents this morning.
</P>
<P>
Sources told Xinhua that under the agreement, all sides will
cut down the number of their army, air forces and units of air
defense forces to no more than 130,400, respectively, within a
depth of 100 kilometers from the border lines.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also sets a maximum quantity limit of major arms
deployed in the areas and defines the ways and timetable of the
reduction, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The border lines between China and the other four countries
total more than 7,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, valid until the end of the year 2020, stipulates
that all parties will reduce military forces in the areas to the
minimum level that suits only defensive needs and accords with
their good-neighborly and friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
All parties of the agreement will not seek unilateral military
superiority and their forces in the areas will not wage any
offensive against one another.
</P>
<P>
They will also exchange regularly relevant military information
about the areas, which will be kept secret to any third party, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mutual supervision will be conducted over implementation of the
agreement, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Chinese Workers Work Five Days A Week (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Of China's 150 million or so
urban employees, some 140 million now enjoy two days-off a week,
thanks to the five-day-work-week system China adopted on May 1,
1995.
</P>
<P>
Chinese workers used to work 48 hours, or six days, a week.
Their work time was first reduced to five and a half days in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Xu Lianyou, director of the Occupation, Safety and Hygiene
Department under the Ministry of Labor, said here today that the
five-day-work-week is now in practice in an overwhelming majority
of the Chinese enterprises and social institutions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that all employees of government departments,
social organizations and institutions in China currently work 40
hours a week.
</P>
<P>
The five-day-work-week has also been adopted by 90 percent of
the state-owned enterprises, over 80 percent of the
collectively-owned enterprises above the county level, and most
foreign-funded and township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, the
five-day-work-week had been introduced in 86.9 percent of the
local enterprises by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of state-owned, collectively-owned, foreign-funded
and private enterprises that had adopted the new system was
respectively 95, 93, and 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The new system has won enthusiastic response among the urban
employees, since it helps create more job opportunities, guarantee
the workers' legitimate rights and interests, and improve their
living quality," said Xu, the director.
</P>
<P>
Another favorable side-effect of the system is that it has
helped to promote the development of the service industry,
especially in tourism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Chinese Workers Work Five Days A Week (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1996, China's domestic tourists totaled 639 million,
bringing 163.8 billion yuan (about 20 billion US dollars) to the
tourism industry. The same two figures for 1994 were only 450
million and 95 billion respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, "weekend tourism" has also added much pressure to the
country's underdeveloped traffic system.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, tens of thousands of people swarmed out of the
city to spend the weekends in neighboring provinces, causing much
trouble for the local railway, air, and road transport departments.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, enterprises that have not adopted
five-day-work-week are mainly some overseas-funded or private
enterprises that lack proper management.
</P>
<P>
"Owners of these enterprises want to increase production and
earn more profits through prolonged work time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there were also a small number of migrant workers
who thought that the new system would prevent them from "earning
more money through doing more work," which Xu called a
"misunderstanding."
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the reduction of work hours has led to an increase
of the average hourly wage, and the labor law ensures that overtime
work is paid more," said Xu, adding that the workers' income would
only rise under the new system.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the State Council, giving full consideration to
the possible difficulties in the introduction of the new system,
had given all enterprises a grace period of two years, which ends
on May 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
"The deadline is just several days to go," he warned. "After
that, anyone that insists on rejecting the new system will receive
administrative penalties from the labor departments in accordance
with the law".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
