<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Develops New Technology for Improving Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli company,
SuperSoyl Lt., has developed a new technology for processing
fresh cow manure into an inert base for artificial soil mixture
(as a peat substitute) for soil improvement, according to the
Israel Export Institute.
</P>
<P>
It can also serve as a replacement for bedding in livestock
padlocks. The process is also applicable to sludge from paper
mills, by itself or together with manure.
</P>
<P>
The company calls the end product "SuperSoyl" and says it
"can be produced at a fraction of the cost of growth media
currently on the market."
</P>
<P>
Unlike other polymer-based artificial soils, it creates no
secondary waste removal problem after use as a growth
medium.
</P>
<P>
The basic system consists of a patented electric reactor, a
mixing tank, a feed pump and a solid/liquid separator. Untreated
waste products are loaded into the tank and mixed with
water. Pumped into the reactor, the mixture undergoes a process
which renders it bacteria-free and ecologically friendly. Next,
it is pumped into the solid/liquid separator.
</P>
<P>
Three configurations are available: a mobile reactor installed
on a trailer for small dairy farms; a fixed version for
continuous operation on large dairy farms and heavy duty
version, consisting of a battery of reactors, for paper mills
and very large dairy farms.
</P>
<P>
SuperSoyl can be spread with conventional farm machinery,
stockpiled, bagged or transported in bulk to end-users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
