<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Grain Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang province, China's
largest grain production base, has taken effective measures to
increase grain production in 1997, according to a provincial
government official.
</P>
<P>
With 8.6 million hectares of cultivated land, Heilongjiang
supplies nearly 20 million tons grain to the country's grain
market annually, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Total grain production was 30.5 million tons last year, an
increase of 4.5 million tons from 1995. The increase accounted for
one third of China's increased grain production.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Heilongjiang met its grain production target for
the 1996-2000 period, four years in advance.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a steady increase in grain production, the province
plans to produce 30 million tons in a normal year, with 32.5
million tons as its goal, a two million ton increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has decided to promote grain
production by increasing the planting acreage to 7.73 million
hectares. It has spread the use of agriculture techniques,
increased per unit yields, improved land contract policies, and
stabilized grain sales channels to help peasants solve the
difficulty in selling grain.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the province will spend about 100 million US dollars
improving 100,000 hectares of low-yield land and reclaiming
133,000 hectares of wasteland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
