<HEADLINE> Pak Against Stopping UN Peace-keeping Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Termination of the United
Nations Military Observers Group in India and Pakistan (UNMOGIP)
"would seriously jeopardize peace and security in a volatile
region like South Asia", a Foreign Office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The termination of this peace-keeping operation would also
seriously impair the UN Security Council's role in the maintenance
of peace as defined by the UN Charter, said the spokesman here
today in a press release issued at the weekly news briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said the UNMOGIP is one of the UN's oldest peace-keeping
operations and has played a useful role in monitoring cease-fire
violations along the Line of Control in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"Any change in the status of the UNMOGIP can be brought about
only by a decision of the Security Council," he said. "It cannot
form part of any deal or benchmarks for UN reform."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan "has taken note of reports regarding a proposed move
by U.S. Senator Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, to link U.S. financial support for UN
peace-keeping operations with interalia termination of the
UNMOGIP", he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Pakistani government has taken up the
matter with the United States as well as the UN secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
