<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, India to Release Boats, Crew in Custody </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and India have reached
 agreement on the release of all boats and crew in the custody of
the two sides, a press release issued by the Foreign Office said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the meeting of the Foreign
Minister of Pakistan and the Minister of External Affairs of India
in New Delhi on April 9, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has provided a list of the Pakistani boats and crew
presently in Indian custody to the Indian High Commission in
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
And it is hoped that arrangements for the simultaneous release
of boats and crew by the two countries would be completed at the
earliest, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan met with his Indian
counterpart Inder Kumar Gujral on April 9 in New Delhi where he
attended a ministerial meeting of the Conference of Non-Aligned
Countries.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers discussed issues of common concern and
decided that a new round of foreign secretary level talks between
the two countries would be held in Islamabad in May.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said here today that the foreign
secretary level talks must be held before the summit of the South
Asian Association of Regional Cooperation to be held in the
Maldives in May.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which is the first step of the normalization of the
Pak-Indian relations, are likely to be held in Islamabad in the
first week of May, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
