<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Faces More Challenges After Exit From IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said here
today that the Philippines will face more challenges after its
graduation from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in June.
</P>
<P>
The country will face more challenges as its economic
performance and credit ratings will be scrutinized more closely by
investors and international partners, the president said in a
speech marking the 100th anniversary of the Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The government will have to prove that even without the IMF's
"carrots and sticks," the Filipinos are capable of doing what
needs to be done to assure the basic stability of the Philippine
economy and financial system, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a time to relax. On the other hand, it is a time to
exercise greater vigilance in managing our financial resources in
order to assure sustained growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the country cannot afford lapses in policies,
warning that "any diminution in domestic support and in
international confidence in the quality of our economic management
will cripple the growth momentum we have gained".
</P>
<P>
The president, however, said the exit from the IMF's
supervision will also test the maturity of the country's systems
of governance in an intensively interdependent world.
</P>
<P>
The exit comes at a time when inflation and interest rates are
running lower than projected, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our fiscal position is stable. Our international reserves are
reassuring. Investor confidence in the prospects of our economy
can only be described as steadfast," he added.
</P>
<P>
The country was allowed to exit from the IMF after more than 30
years of supervision under the international organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
