<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President: No Common Ground Found Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- There has been no common
ground or convergence of views on the Cyprus problem between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides after six weeks of U.N.-led
proximity talks, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark Wednesday night after a marathon session
of the National Council, the top advisory body to the President
on the handling of the Cyprus problem, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the U.N.-led proximity talks, which started on
March 10, President Clerides said that "we began discussing some of
the fundamental aspects of the Cyprus problem and realized that
there is substantial difference between the two sides."
</P>
<P>
He said that "we have not started discussing Ghali's Set of
Ideas."
</P>
<P>
The Set of Ideas, put forward by former U.N. Secretary General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali in 1992, includes the constitutional aspects
of a federation, security and guarantee, territorial adjustment,
displaced persons and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The proximity talks, Clerides said, were concentrated on good-will
measures for the creation of a better climate between Greek
and Turkish Cypriots on the issue of sovereignty and other
issues, on which common ground has not been reached.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, President Clerides said that "today
we are discussing the Cyprus problem on the basis of a
letter by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan."
</P>
<P>
The letter, Clerides said, stresses that "High Level
Agreements (reached in 1977 and 1979 by Presidents Makarios and
Spyros Kyprianou and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
respectively), relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions as well
as the Set of Ideas and other ideas discussed so far, are on the
negotiating table."
</P>
<P>
Clerides noted that the U.N. Set of Ideas contains important
negative elements which could not lead to a lasting and viable
solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
According to the local reports, no decisions were announced
at the end of Wednesday's National Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, the Council, comprises all political party leaders,
reaffirmed its stand that the government should continue with
the ongoing proximity talks, and it will evaluate the result
of the talks before the Greek Cypriot side enters direct talks
with Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Annan has looked forward to sponsoring a face-to-face talks
between leaders of the two communities by middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
