<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pottery Figures Admired By Distinguished Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The recent tour of Mauritian
Premier Navin Ramgoolam to Xi'an to see the world-famous clay
figures known as the "eighth wonder of the world," brings the
number of distinguished guests who have made the trip to 100.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40 million people from around the world have visited the
life-sized terracotta horses and armored warriors, located one and
a half kilometers east of the tomb of Qin Shihuang, the founder of
the Qin dynasty (221-207 BC).
</P>
<P>
The clay figures were discovered in 1974, and opened for
public display five years later.
</P>
<P>
Among the many leading figures who have visited the
historical site over the past 20 years are former US President
Ronald Reagan, Britain's Queen Elizabeth II and former Japanese
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Rene Chirac, now French President, called the clay
characters "the eighth wonder in the world" during his 1978 visit
as French Prime Minister to Xi'an, which is also the point of
origin of the ancient "Silk Road."
</P>
<P>
In 1976, former Singapore Premier Lee Kuan Yew visited the
excavation tunnel after he got word of the discovery of the
terracotta figures.
</P>
<P>
Upon seeing them, he exclaimed, "These wonderful things are the
pride of Chinese nation!"
</P>
<P>
And German Prime Minister Helmut Kohl after his tour remarked,
"I admire the Chinese culture and traditions shining behind the
pottery wonders, and seeing them is an important experience for
me."
</P>
<P>
The manager of the terracotta display said that some of the
figures have been sent from China to more than 30 countries and
regions for exhibition, and the clay characters were dubbed
"Chinese cultural envoys" by foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Fueling China's Hydropower Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China has 23 hydropower projects
in operation or under construction by utilizing foreign funds
worth nearly 3.7 billion billion US dollars, with a total
generating capacity over 18.84 million kw.
</P>
<P>
"China has the richest hydropower resources in the world, with
exploitable water energy resources estimated at 376 million kwh,
ranking first in the world," said Wang Xinmao, a senior Chinese
hydropower expert, at the just-concluded World Energy Council Asia
Pacific Regional Forum.
</P>
<P>
He said that at the end of 1995, China had completed 13
hydropower projects with a combined generating capacity of 5.62
million kw by introducing 854 million US dollars. Another five,
with total generating capacity of 5.48 million kw and a combined
foreign investment of 1.44 billion US dollars, had gone into
partial operation.
</P>
<P>
Presently, there are still five hydropower projects under
construction with a total capacity of 8.1 million kw, which will
involve 1.396 billion US dollars in foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
China has made remarkable achievements in developing its
hydropower industry over the past four decades, particularly since
the launching of the reform and opening-up drive in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The total generating capacity and the annual electricity output
have risen from 163,000 kw and 710 million kwh in 1949 to 52.17
million kw and 186.8 billion kwh, respectively in 1995. As a
result, China ranked third in hydropower generating capacity and
production in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, the expert noted that much still needed to be done to
exploit China's enormous hydropower resources. By the end of 1995,
the country's total hydropower generating capacity was only 13.8
percent of the total exploitable potential, which is lower than
the world's average.
</P>
<P>
According to its medium- and long-term hydropower development
plan, China will develop add a total hydropower capacity of 70
million kw by the year 2000. By 2010, the figure will rise to 125
million kw, or 33.1 percent of the country's exploitable
hydropower resources.
</P>
<P>
The expert said that an annual installed capacity of 3.5
million kw will be added, on average, in the remaining years
of the century. And between 2000 and 2010, the annual installed
hydropower capacity will increase to five million kw.
</P>
<P>
The ever-growing hydropower industry will provide a vast market
for foreign enterprises and consortiums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 08:26 </DATE_TIME>
