<HEADLINE> Pak Denies Engineering "Third Force" in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today denied a report
alleging that the country was engineering a "third force" to rule
Afghanistan in the event of Taliban's failure.
</P>
<P>
The report is "totally incorrect and baseless", said a Foreign
Office spokesman here today at the weekly news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has been trying and is still trying to help resolve
the Afghan conflict under the auspices of the United Nations, but
it has never interfered in the Afghan internal affairs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Masood, defense minister of the ousted Afghan government,
reportedly charged recently that Pakistan was attempting to forge
a political union between former Afghan prime minister Gulbuddin
Hekmatyar and ex-communist defense minister Shahnawaz Tanai.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, the Islamic student militia, now holds more than
two thirds of the Afghan territory while the anti-Taliban alliance
led by mainly by Masood occupies the remaining one third in
northern Afghanistan.  
</P>
