<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President on Five-Nation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today described as having "major political and military
significance" the Agreement on Mutual Reduction of Military Forces
in the Border Areas between China and the four countries of
Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by the presidents of the five nations
here today, represents "the fruit of the constant development and
consolidation of China's good-neighborly relations, friendship and
mutually-beneficial cooperation with the four countries," Jiang
said at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, a result of more than seven years of
negotiations, is the first inter-state document in the Asia
Pacific region on the mutual reduction of military forces.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the signing of the agreement serves the
interest of maintaining peace, stability and tranquillity in the
border areas between China and the four countries, and
facilitating further growth of good-neighborly relations,
friendship, mutual trust on the basis of equality and
mutually-beneficial cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it "offers a security model different from the
cold-war mentality in safeguarding peace, security and stability
in the Asia Pacific region and the world at large, thereby opening
up a useful way for the enhancement of mutual trust among states,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people love peace and long for development," the
president said. He stressed that China was ready to work together
with peoples all over the world to make positive contributions to
the establishment of a peaceful and stable, just and equitable new
international political and economic order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
