<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A trade agreement recently signed by Israel and
Turkey has paved the way for the lifting of trade barriers and
tariffs on a wide range of goods, other than agricultural
products, reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry officials have said that they expect
the new pact to quadruple trade between the two countries over
the next four years, saying that trade will increase to 2
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The latest agreement marks a continuation of a considerable
turnabout by Turkey's Islamic government. When elected into office
less than a year ago, it adopted a clearly unenthusiastic
approach toward bilateral relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Yigal Hoesman, President of the Israeli Diamond
Manufacturers Association, has been holding discussions with
Jordanian businessmen over the past six months regarding the
possibility of setting up joint ventures for processing small
diamonds, reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
Hoesman rejected claims that the joint ventures would take
employment away from the local industry, saying that it should
be noted that the discussions are about polishing facilities
which will address the industrial sector which has not existed
in Israel for several years. These are small stones which are
not currently produced in Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said that the talks were initiated by Jordanian
businessmen. Hoesman accompanied Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
on his latest trip to Jordan when Hoesman met officials of
the Jordanian Investment Center.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Dutch government has approved the transfer of
funds for the continuation of the Middle East Competitive
Advantage research project, reported bi-weekly Israel Business
Today.
</P>
<P>
Holand also provided funding for the first phase of the
project which is designed to locate and define competitive
advantages in Israel, Jordan, Egypt and the Palestinian autonomous
areas.
</P>
<P>
The research work is based on a model devised by Harvard
University Professor Michael Porter and is managed by Porter and
Israeli businessman Yagil Weinberg. To date, the project has
found areas of cooperation which would be of benefit to the
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The marine equipment market in the Gulf region
was expected to reach some 14 million U.S. dollars this year,
according to a press release available here today.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the Gulf market for jet boats,
personal watercraft and water sports equipment and accessories
will approach 14 million dollars in 1997, said the report by
Dubai World Trade Center which will host a Middle East
international boat show in May.
</P>
<P>
This is a consecutive 20 percent growth on average during
the past eight years, said the center based in Dubai, one of
the seven sheikdoms of the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The Gulf countries every year attract many water sport
races, mainly jet ski races, and the UAE alone hosts six major
races annually. These activities have increased the market size
of marine leisure equipment in the region rapidly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
