<HEADLINE> Troops Sent to Curb Banditry in Northwestern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A group of Navy soldiers
from here has arrived in Kigoma, northwestern Tanzania for
patrolling along the coast of Lake Tanganyika against the
mounting banditry there.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper reported today that the move is one of
the government's efforts to strengthen security against armed
gangsters who were believed to come from the neighboring Zaire
and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
About 67 cases of robberies and other forms of theft occurred
between 1992 and 1996, the regional authorities said, calling for
help from the government.
</P>
<P>
Reports in the area said last week local businessmen sailing
across the lake from Burundi's capital Bujumbura were robbed of
cash and goods by an extremist Hutu faction called CNDD.
</P>
<P>
The extremists threatened to sink any ship trying to ferry
goods to Bujumbura, saying they are monitoring and supervising
sanctions imposed on the Burundi military junta last year.
</P>
<P>
The extremists were ready to sink any vessels trying to defy
their threat.
</P>
<P>
The regional Hutu extremists do not recognize the easing of
economic sanctions against Major Buyoya's government as declared
in the Arusha summit last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
