<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Calls for Better Trade Ties with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Zimbabwe should
continue to pursue policies for boosting their trade and economic
cooperation and to try to find a lasting solution to end regional
conflicts, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a state banquet in honor to him by Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe, Moi said he hopes that his four-day state visit
starting Wednesday would enhance the already good relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said soon after Zimbabwe attained its independence,
Kenya-Zimbabwe trade ties have been strengthened and a number of
bilateral trade agreements concerned have been signed.
</P>
<P>
On the political field, Moi said "I recall with satisfaction
the efforts our two countries made towards the resolution of the
conflict in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
"More recently we have worked together in the search for peace
and stability in the Great Lakes region and in particular, the
on-going crisis in Zaire," he continued.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two countries to continue to support the efforts
of the U.N. and the OAU in their efforts for a peaceful solution
to end conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that peace will be restored in Burundi,
Somalia and Sudan, adding his country was committed to the
realization of peace and security in southern Sudan. 
</P>
