<HEADLINE> "Konka" Color TV, China's Name-Brand Electronic Product </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The "Konka" televisions, which
are manufactured by a Hong Kong-funded firm in south China's
Guangdong Province, has been designated as a name-brand product.
</P>
<P>
The Konka Group, set up in 1979 in Shenzhen, received the
name-brand trade mark from the State Administration for Industry
and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The group, a Guangdong-Hong Kong joint venture, is the
first Chinese color TV maker to meet ISO 9001 accreditation
standards.
</P>
<P>
The group, which was listed on a stock exchange in 1992, has
become one of the country's ten major overseas-funded enterprises
in terms of earning foreign exchange from exports. It now turns
out one-fifth to the country's color TV exports.
</P>
<P>
Konka group, with investments totalling four billion yuan, is
listed among the country's leading 500 enterprises and top 100
companies with the most advanced technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The group produced 2.8 million color TVs last year and earned
six billion yuan in sales, occupying nearly a 20 percent share of
the country's color TV market.
</P>
<P>
It developed more than 40 new types of color TVs annually to
cater to the various needs of customers.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Konka, China now has two other name-brand
color TVs: "Panda" made in Nanjing, capital in east China's
Jiangsu Province, and "Changhong" produced in Mianyang in
southwest China's Sichuan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
