<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Supports Myanmar's Entry Into ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today Malaysia would strongly support
Myanmar's inclusion into the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) regardless of which political party runs the
government there.
</P>
<P>
He said his country's support for Myanmar's inclusion into the
regional grouping was not based on the type of government or
individuals running the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are not supporting the government or individuals, we are
just supporting the inclusion of Myanmar into ASEAN, " Mahathir
told a news conference held after he chaired a National
Information Technology Council meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the remarks while responding to reporters'
questions on Malaysia's stand on Myanmar joining ASEAN, which
presently comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia would certainly make a strong stand on the
inclusion of Myanmar at the ASEAN ministerial meeting in July and
the informal ASEAN summit at the end of the year, both events to
be held here.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers are scheduled to meet here on May 31 to
discuss when to admit Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos into the regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia, as an independent country, would behave
like one on the issue of Myanmar's entry into ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know about other members of ASEAN but I certainly will
make a very strong stand on this. I don't want people to tell me
whom I should have as a friend and whom should be my enemy. I
develop my own enemy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the United States decided to impose
sanctions against Myanmar by banning new U.S. investments in that
country.
</P>
<P>
To a question on why Malaysia supported sanctions against South
Africa, not sanctions against Myanmar, Mahathir said, "When we
supported sanction against South Africa, that sanction was
actually demanded by the ANC (African National Congress), the
black in South Africa themselves. They wanted the sanction as they
were prepared to pay the price for it."
</P>
<P>
But in the case of Myanmar, the Myanmar people did not invite
sanctions, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions will affect the people not the government. The
government will live in fine style if they want to. For example,
sanctions against Iraq have affected the people of Iraq and not
the government of Iraq or the leaders of Iraq. So we shouldn't do
that kind of thing to the people," Mahathir said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
