<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Sector Grows In First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's steel industry witnessed
steady growth in the first quarter of this year, today's "China
Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper quotes a senior official from the
Ministry of Metallurgical Industry (MMI) as saying that in the
first three months, China produced 25.43 million tons of steel, up 5.4
percent or 1.3 million tons over that of the corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The output of pig iron grew by 1.09 million tons hitting 2.65
million tons and rolled steel grew by 1.69 million tons reaching
2.208 million tons during the period.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium steel enterprises produced 1.08 million tons
more than they produced during the corresponding period last year,
accounting for 83 percent of the total increase in output.
</P>
<P>
The production and sales ratio of the top 10 steel producers
reached approximately 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the January-March period, according to the paper, the
ratio of continuous casting products, an indicator of the
industry's technical level, reached 58.27 percent, 7.12 percentage
points higher than the figure in the corresponding period last
year.
</P>
<P>
China's goal is to achieve a ratio of 80 percent by the end of
this century. During the first quarter, China produced 14.82
million tons of continuous cast billet, an increase of 2.46
million tons over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
China exported 1.72 million tons of rolled steel and steel
billets during the January-March period, a jump of 360,000 tons
over the same period last year, according to statistics released
by Chinese customs.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, China imported 2.79 million tons of
rolled steel and 50,000 tons of steel billets. This brings a net
import of 1.87 million tons, 760,000 tons less than was imported
during the corresponding period last year, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Government Reaps More Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
today reported a 3.1 billion-dollar (2.14 billion U.S. dollars)
operating surplus in the first three quarters of the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The surplus, for the period ending March, was 55 million
dollars (37.95 million U.S. dollars) more than forecast.
</P>
<P>
The government said its expenses in the nine months were 0.7
percent lower than forecast, standing at 182 million dollars
(125.58 million U.S. dollars), but non-tax revenue for the period
was 104 million dollars (71.76 million U.S. dollars), 4.6 percent
ahead of forecast.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises contributed 66 million dollars (45.54
million U.S. dollars) more than Treasury forecast. However, tax
revenue was only 275 million dollars (189.75 million U.S.
dollars), or 1.1 percent lower than expected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
