<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five-Nation Accord on Border Arms Reduction Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- An agreement on mutual reduction
of military forces in border areas between China and four
countries, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, was
signed here today.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of the five countries inked the document in the
Kremlin. It was the first agreement of its kind in the Asia
Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was a result of over seven years of negotiations
between China and the four countries.
</P>
<P>
It followed the agreement on confidence-building in the
military field in border areas signed by the five presidents in
Shanghai, China, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Sources told Xinhua that under the agreement, all sides will
cut down the number of their army, air forces and units of air
defense forces to no more than 130,400, respectively, within a
depth of 100 kilometers from the border lines.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also sets a maximum quantity limit of major arms
deployed in the areas and defines the ways and timetable of the
reduction, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The boder lines between China and the other four countries
total more than 7,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, valid until the end of the year 2020, stipulates
that all parties will reduce military forces in the areas to the
minimum level that suits only defensive needs and accords with
their good-neighborly and friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
All parties of the agreement will not seek unilateral military
superiority and their forces in the areas will not wage any
offensive against one another.
</P>
<P>
They will also exchange regularly relevant military information
about the areas, which will be kept secret to any third party, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mutual supervision will be conducted over implementation of the
agreement, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bank Granted Restricted Banking License by HKMA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Lloyds Bank Plc (LB)
has been granted a restricted banking license by the Hong Kong
Monetary Authority (HKMA), a HKMA spokesman announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The grant increased the number of restricted license banks in
HK to 64, he said.
</P>
<P>
LB is a wholly owned subsidiary of Lloyds TSB Group Plc, one of
the Big Five Banks in Britain and ranking among the top 50 banks
in the world in terms of total assets and tier one capital.
</P>
<P>
LB has an extensive domestic branch network and maintains a
presence in 18 countries including the Netherlands, Switzerland,
Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a three-tier system of deposit-taking
institutions -- licensed banks, restricted license banks and
deposit-taking companies -- which are collectively called
authorized institutions, while the HKMA, the de facto central bank
in Hong Kong, acts as the licensing authority. 
</P>
