<HEADLINE> Qinhuangdao Port Aims High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Qinhuangdao Port in north
China's Hebei Province plans to build more than 40 berths in the
remaining years of this century, to bring its annual handling
capacity to nearly 125 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The port is the starting point and a hub for the massive coal
transportation from north to south, and also the largest coal
shipping port in the world.
</P>
<P>
Since China's reform and opening-up policy was implemented in
1979, three modern coal berths with handling capacities of ten
million, 20 million, and 30 million tons, respectively, have been
built there.
</P>
<P>
The port now has 38 berths. Statistics show that it in 1996 it
was capable of handling 83.1 million tons of cargo.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the port has decided to jointly build a
container company with a Hong Kong firm, involving a total
investment of ten million US dollars. So far, the port has handled
nearly 10,000 TEUs of containers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
