<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Headway In Capital Construction (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Since 1982, China has drawn up
strategic plans for capital construction every year, encouraging
development in some sectors according to national economic and
social dvelopment needs. The government has given priority to
these capital projects and provided neccessary financial,
material, and trasportation aids.
</P>
<P>
These capital construction projects are aimed at fuelling the
country's economic growth, economists say. During the Eighth
Five-Year Plan, China put a total of 2.4 trillion yuan into
capital construction, and finished work on 700 key projects.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's economy has had double-digit growth
in the last few years and has ranked first in the world in annual
output of some major industrial products, such as coal, iron and
steel, and cement.
</P>
<P>
Technology in all the sectors of national economy has been
improved, thanks partly to overseas investment and advanced
technology, economists say.
</P>
<P>
"China will focus attention on construction of infrasturtural
projects in the coming years, as a decisive factor of its economic
growth," an official from the State Planning Committee says.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-2000 period, China will need nine trillion yuan
in investment in the state sector, which accounts for about 60
percent of the country's total in fixed assets. Priority will be
given to agriculture, energy, transpotation, petroleum,
electronics, and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jinhua, director of the State Planning Committee, says
that China will take further steps to open up and use overseas
funds for capital construction in the coming years. Chen says that
the country will continue to seek foreign government loans and
loans from international banking groups; in the meantime, it will
make use of overseas commercial loans in a gradual and steady way
in addition to encouraging direct overseas investment in
infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
