<HEADLINE> Shenzhen to Reduce Land Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen City of South China's
Guangdong Province has decided to reduce this year's land supply
to 11.26 million sq m, a drop of 12.6 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
This was learned from the Third Session of the Second Shenzhen
City People's Congress which was convened recently.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the city only earned 40 million
yuan from the paid transfers of state-owned land use rights in
1996, meeting only 23.5 percent of the city's budgetary plan for
the year, and a plunge of 76.5 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Local officials blamed land development enterprises being in
arrears with paying land use fees in the wake of a sluggish real
estate market.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen sold on the open market apartments and house
construction designs with a combined floor space of 3.25 million
sq m in 1996, including 1.87 million sq m of apartments already
completed.
</P>
<P>
The city has planned to invest 13.6 billion yuan in
constructing open market apartments this year, with the focus
going to the construction of low-cost partments. The city will
suspend the issue of permits to construct various kinds of office
buildings and training centers, and strictly control the
construction of luxury real estate development projects.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen will also try to lower construction costs of open
market flats, reduce burdens both on land developers and flats
buyers, explore new financial sources for housing to encourage
consumption in housing this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shenzhen will also step up cooperation with real
estate developers and intermediary agencies in Hong Kong, and
simplify exit and entry procedures to attract Hong Kong investors
to build flats on a cooperative basis or to buy them in Shenzhen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
