<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanction Won't Affect Myanmar's Entry into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore indicated today that
the United States sanctions against Myanmar will not have direct
impact on the country's entry into the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
In response to press queries on the matter, a Singapore Foreign
Ministry spokesman reiterated that the timing of the admission of
Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar into the ASEAN depended on their
readiness to join the organization.
</P>
<P>
"They must be prepared to accede to the ASEAN economic and
non-economic agreements on admission," the spokesman said, adding
that the ASEAN foreign ministers will meet in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia, on May 31 to discuss various ASEAN issues, including the
expansion of the group.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that ASEAN considers constructive
engagement as the best way to facilitate Myanmar's economic
liberalization which in turn will bring about further internal
changes.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the view that sanctions only work in cases
where the economy of a country is plugged to the global economy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced the
sanctions in Washington Tuesday, citing the Myanmar ruling junta's
repression of the pro-democracy opposition led by Aung San Suu
Kyi.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that the U.S. decision to clamp
sanctions on Myanmar is unlikely to hurt the economy which is
increasingly dependent on its Asian trading partners, as many of
the analysts believed that the U.S. sanctions would have little
bite given the small number of American companies currently doing
business in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
They said that this would only open the door further for their
Asian and European competitors.
</P>
<P>
In the region, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh said Yangon's entry into
the ASEAN will not be affected by the U.S. sanction.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
