<HEADLINE> U.S. to Put India on Watch List Over Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- India will figure in this
year's Special 301 priority watch list prepared by the U.S. trade
representative for failing to provide adequate and effective
intellectual property rights protection, a government official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
India could be elevated to a higher "priority foreign country"
in view of its failure to meet the trade-related intellectual
property rights (TRIPS) obligations under the World Trade
Organization (WTO), he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, in a complaint filed with the WTO last year,
alleged that India has failed to provide patents protection for
pharmaceutical, chemical and agricultural products. It also
charged that India has not legislatively established mailbox and
marketing exclusivity systems in accordance with articles 70(8)
and 70(9) of the TRIPS agreement.  
</P>
