<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OSCE Official Optimistic Over Treaty Revision Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO and Russia could reach
agreement in their talks on revising the Treaty on Reducing
Conventional Armed Forces in Europe before May 27 when the
military alliance is to hold a summit in Paris, western diplomats
here said today.
</P>
<P>
Austria's national news agency reported Negotiators from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) as
saying that NATO would not only come up with measures to build
trust with Moscow, but also give up deploying nuclear weapons and
a large number of combat troops on the territories of new member
states.
</P>
<P>
But it will not commit itself to limiting its conventional
troops in Europe to the present level of 50 percent after its
enlargement into Central and Eastern Europe, as Russia demands.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which treats the revision of the treaty as one of the
preconditions for the eastward expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, insists on determining the ceiling of the
alliance's overall conventional weapons and troops through
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The talks began on January 21 in Vienna and is expected to end
in July next year.
</P>
<P>
The Treaty on Reducing Conventional Armed Forces in Europe,
signed in 1990 between NATO and the defunct Warsaw Pact countries
in Paris, stipulated for a 50-50 division of conventional weapons
between east and west European countries.
</P>
<P>
NATO claims that the number of its conventional forces at
present has not actually reached 50 percent, saying it will
surpass the limit after its enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Besides, front runners for NATO membership, generally regarded
as Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, demanded during the
negotiations their conventional forces and weapons be modernized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Self-Claimed Daughter of Emperor Hirohito Cheats With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- An elderly Japanese woman who
claimed to be a daughter of the late Emperor Hirohito tried,
together with five men, to cheat foreign banks here of a sum
amounting to 1.27 trillion yen (about 9.7 billion U.S. dollars at
the current exchange rate), but ended up in court, local
newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said a district court heard on Wednesday that the
group purportedly tried to open accounts with the banks with a
forged bank draft for the amount. But their ambitious scam failed
to take off because all the banks suspected the transaction and
made their own checks.
</P>
<P>
The banks discovered that the purported bank draft had not been
issued by the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank in Tokyo and reported the
matter to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The female mastermind, 68-year-old Madam Sadako Okada, had
claimed to be the daughter of the Japanese monarch's unofficial
wife. The court convicted her last year and sentenced her to 18
months in jail. But she died in the New Changi Hospital in
Singapore two days before her release on March 13 this year.
</P>
<P>
Okada, who claimed to have inherited her fortune from the late
emperor, also wore a 16-petal chrysanthemum pin, the supposed
symbol of Emperor Hirohito, who died in early 1989.
</P>
<P>
The five men accused were facing up to 10 years in jail if they
are convicted of the crime, the reports said. They are Hsiao Li
Tung, 61, and Chao Ping Yuan, 50, from Taiwan; Seiji Shudo, 61,
and Taiji Nomura, 59, from Japan; and Heng Bah Bee, 49, from
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
They reportedly said they believed the bank draft was genuine
and that Okada, whom they met by introduction, was truly a
royalty.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the prosecution, the five men, with
Okada, had tried to cheat three foreign banks based here between
January and February last year. The foreign banks involved were
the Republic National Bank of New York, American Express Bank and
the Union Bank of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
During meetings with bank officers, Okada was introduced as a
royalty to facilitate the cashing of the bank draft issued seven
years ago. But the bank officers had doubts because they wondered
why Okada did not cash the bank draft then in Japan, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
On February 27 last year, the Commercial Affairs Department of
Singapore received a tip-off on the group and rounded up Okada and
the five accused after a sting operation at one of the banks in
March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
