<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Build First Oil Refinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will start to build its
first oil refinery later this year, at an estimated cost of 1.2
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The refinery, in the central province of Quang Ngai, will meet
domestic demands, media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the Dung Quat refinery will process 6.5 million
tons of domestic crude oil a year, producing products such as
liquefied gas, unleaded petrol, kerosene, aircraft fuel and
propylene, for the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes that the refinery will meet 65 percent of
domestic demand by the time it becomes operational in 2002, and 50
percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Petrovietnam has been authorized to conduct a feasibility study
for the construction, and the study is expected to be completed by
the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the cost of the project, which was expected
to last about five years, would come from domestic sources and the
remainder from foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign investors had promised to take part in the
project, but withdrew later as they could not meet the
government's requirements.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is still leaving open the possibility of a joint
venture with foreign partners while it goes ahead with the plan to
build the refinery by itself, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
