<HEADLINE> Talks on Hydro-Power Project in Nepal Deadlocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Talks between the Nepali
government and a foreign promoter over a commercial hydro-power
project have turned out a deadlock as the two sides have big
differences on issues like payments and the operation term, the
local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on the West Seti project ended Tuesday with
the government refusing to grant export license for the project,
which is to be developed by Snowy Mountain Engineering Co. of
Australia, reports quoted Nepali officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 750-megawatt project, located about 300 km west of here, is
Nepal's first export-oriented hydro-power project with an
estimated cost of over 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is also the country's first hydro-power project to be
developed totally by a foreign investor on BOT
(Build-Operate-Transfer) basis, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The project's Australian promoter expects to export all the
product of the project to neighboring India, which is facing a
widespread power supply shortage in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
However, the nearly one-week talks on the export authorization
letter for the project could not yield agreement between the two
sides on several crucial issues including the export rates,
compensation terms for delayed payments and the project's
operation term by the developer, sources said.
</P>
<P>
An official from Nepal's Water Resources Ministry said
Wednesday that the Australian company still wanted the export
license by suggesting the disagreements be listed separately for
later negotiations.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the company has threatened to withdraw from
the project if the government would not make concessions on these
issues.
</P>
<P>
The next round of talks between the two sides is scheduled for
early next month, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
