<HEADLINE> U.S. Ban on Myanmar Not to Affect ASEAN: Thai Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States' ban on new
U.S. investments in Myanmar has no influence over the process of
admitting Myanmar into the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN), Thai officials said.
</P>
<P>
The United States is entitled to impose sanctions against
Myanmar, just as ASEAN is entitled to admit it, said Saroj
Chavanaviraj, permanent secretary of the Thai Foreign Affairs
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has already committed itself to admitting Myanmar,
Cambodia and Laos at the same time, although ASEAN foreign
ministers are due to discuss the timing of the entry in Kuala
Lumpur on May 31, Saroj was quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
However, the Thai official believed that the U.S. ban could
affect the future economic cooperation between ASEAN and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. earlier this week announced its decision to ban new
U.S. investment in Myanmar until Myanmar makes improvement in its
human rights situation.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Thai Commerce Ministry officials said
Wednesday that Myanmar has agreed to implement all economic
agreements related to ASEAN membership.
</P>
<P>
The pacts include the ASEAN free trade area (AFTA) agreement,
the framework agreement on cooperation in services, the framework
agreement on cooperation in intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also has to accept the principle of most favored nation
and support transparency in trade.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials said that the Myanmar government had submitted
its inclusion list of products whose import tariffs would be cut
below five percent within 10 years after it joins the AFTA.
However, they said that Myanmar's first list is not complete and
it will present an amended one before July when ASEAN foreign
ministers meet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
