<HEADLINE> Thailand's Export Slump Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export slump continued
in the first two months of this year, causing further concern
among finance and monetary officials.
</P>
<P>
The country's export growth for the first two months fell to
minus 0.3 percent from the same period of last year, as
year-on-year growth of exports in February fell 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's export sector's growth was near zero.
</P>
<P>
The figures for the sluggish export in January-February dashed
hopes of a turnaround of the Thai economy and officials fear that
they might have to significantly revise downward economic growth
predictions for 1997, which are already low.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Thai currency baht's appreciation against the
German mark and the Japanese yen, which have lowered the
competitiveness of Thai products in the two markets, monetary
officials attribute falling exports to the poorer-than-expected
performance of the commodity sector, particularly tapioca and
rubber which are mired in price slumps. Rice exports dropped even
though prices were higher.
</P>
<P>
Deputy prime minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan on
Wednesday urged the Commerce Ministry to consult with exporters
over the performance of the export sector in the first quarter and
to review all overseas orders for Thai goods.
</P>
<P>
He said measures will have to be introduced to jump start
sluggish export sectors.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic sluggishness, Amnuay said that at least
the government's main policy thrust of economic stability has been
achieved, with both inflation and the current account deficit
expected to fall in the first quarter of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
