<HEADLINE> 560 Tons of Illegal Timber Seized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A total of 560 tons of illegal
timber has been seized by the Myanmar authorities in three areas
in the country in March-April, according to official reports.
</P>
<P>
Of the seized timber, 427 tons of teak, padauk and tamalan
(hard wood) were confiscated by local army units and the forestry
authorities in villages in Lashio, Shan state of Myanmar, on March
23.
</P>
<P>
Another 56 tons of timber and 800 baskets of charcoal were
seized during a raid in villages in South-West Command area on
April 3-4, official paper The New Light of Myanmar said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 77 tons of illegally traded logs and sawn
timber were also seized by the authorities in the Bago division
earlier this month, according to earlier official report.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar enacted the Forest Law in 1992, it has restricted
export of logs, banning the private sector exporting teak logs.
</P>
<P>
However, export of value-added wood-products is encouraged.
</P>
