<HEADLINE> Environmental Improvements Made at China's Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Six years ago, all a person could
see around the Jungar Coal Mines in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region was an endless sea of yellow earth.
</P>
<P>
Now, however, when you enter the coalmine area, you're likely
to see green grass and trees. How did this happen?
</P>
<P>
"What we used to worry about was whether the development of the
coal mine would cause the environment to deteriorate," said a coal
mine official, "but those worries don't exist now."
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, the local government has spent 13 million yuan
(1.57 million US dollars) on protecting the mine area from soil
erosion. The efforts paid off with a forest coverage rate now of
60 percent. The local government attributed this to joint efforts
by environmental protection departments and the mine
administration.
</P>
<P>
Before any work is done on the coal mine now, environmental
protection departments make a feasibility study on impact on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The Dongsheng Coalmine, a large mine in the region, has also
seen environmental improvements. Nearly 80 ha of green areas have
been built in the mine area, helping control wind and sand damage.
</P>
<P>
The Jungar and Dongsheng mines are located in the northern part
of the loess plateau, which is famous for its severe soil
erosion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
