<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Helping Poor Farmers Improve Living Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai, a
remote province with a harsh environment, has a large population
living below the poverty line with an annual per capita income of
less than 500 yuan and grain quota of less than 300 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the only relief the province could give was some
money, and when that was used up, the farmers fell back into
poverty.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, the local government began to concentrate funds and
personnel resources in helping farmers improve arable land and
other production conditions. Last year, it helped 520,000 poor
farmers.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 80,000 ha of terraced land and 879 projects for
providing drinking water for farmers have been completed and roads
and electric power lines have been improved.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the total income for poor rural areas increased nearly
three-fold over the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
