<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Students Over 40 Attend Universities in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of students over 40
years old has increased considerably in Costa Rican universities,
a study published today found.
</P>
<P>
At the University of Costa Rica, the most prestigious in the
country with nearly 26,000 students, 936 of the students that
registered last year, or 3.6 percent, were over 40.
</P>
<P>
The percentage is higher in other national universities.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, the percentage was only 1.5 percent,
according to the study made by the National Council of University
Presidents.
</P>
<P>
National universities expect their students to be between 18-24
years of age, but now 40 percent of their students are above that
age bracket.
</P>
<P>
The study found that older people go to college to get a degree
in another field of study or do graduate work in their old major.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 percent of the students over 40 years old already
have a university degree, the study shows.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed that higher life expectations have
motivated many of these students to attend university lectures
again.
</P>
<P>
The study also revealed that young people are inclined to learn
sciences, such as physics, mathematics or computers, while older
students usually study arts, linguistics or teaching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
