<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Steps in to Prop Rice Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is stepping
in with two incentives planned for local rice millers and
exporters to prop up the falling rice exports in the country.
</P>
<P>
As one of the incentives, the government will offer loans with
a five-percent interest rate for rice millers and traders who
agree to purchase at least on million tons of paddy, Thai Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan said.
</P>
<P>
As for the other incentive, the Thai government will offer
loans with a five-percent interest rate to exporters who will
export at least 500,000 tons of rice during a designated period,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today said that the measures proved to be
successful last year, so the Rice Policy Committee decided to
re-introduce them for this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Thai Rice Exporters Association, Thailand
exported 1.04 million tons of rice in the first quarter of this
year, slumping by about 30.2 percent compared with the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's rice export value during the period posted 10.813
billion baht (about 432.5 million U.S. dollars), dropping 16.8
percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the surging price of Thai rice on
the world market to the slump.
</P>
<P>
Local rice exporters believed that Thailand's rice exports are
expected to turn better in the second quarter, hitting 410,000 to
450,000 tons per month.
</P>
<P>
The major markets for good quality rice will be China and Iran
while the Philippines is expected to buy a significant amount of
low-grade rice from Thailand, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
