<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (41-42) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (41-42)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Who can hold the posts of Chief Justice of the Court
of Final Appeal and Chief Judge of the High Court, and under what
circumstances will they be removed?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal and the
Chief Judge of the High Court of the Hong Kong SAR must be Chinese
citizens who are permanent residents of the region with no right
of abode in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal of the Hong Kong
SAR may be investigated only for inability to discharge his or her
duties, or for misbehavior, by a tribunal appointed by the Chief
Executive and consisting of not fewer than five local judges.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Justice may be removed by the Chief Executive on the
tribunal's recommendation and in accordance with procedures
prescribed in the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
In the appointment or removal of judges of the Court of Final
Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court of the Hong Kong
SAR, the Chief Executive must, in addition to following procedures
as prescribed in the Basic Law, obtain the endorsement of the
Legislative Council and report such appointment or removal to the
NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Question: Which court in the Hong Kong SAR has the power of
final adjudication?
</P>
<P>
Answer: When China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong, the power of final adjudication of the Hong Kong SAR
will be vested with its Court of Final Appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
