<HEADLINE> Andean Community Vows to Create Common Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUCRE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The four member countries of the
Andean Community trade bloc today declared their commitment to
create a regional common market and to liberalize and expand
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
The commitment is made in the Sucre Act which was signed by the
presidents of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela at the end
of their two-day summit in Sucre.
</P>
<P>
The four countries also deplored Peru's decision to withdraw
from the group, saying that a great deal of effort had been made
over the past five years to facilitate Peru's entry into the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Peru announced on April 11 it was leaving the group, claiming
it was not living up to its mission of creating freer trade in the
region. But the move came after other members rejected its
proposals for entering the group's common external tariff.
</P>
<P>
The Sucre Act was signed by Presidents Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada
of Bolivia, Ernesto Samper of Colombia, Fabian Alarcon of Ecuador
and Rafael Caldera of Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian President Ernesto Perez Balladares attended the summit
as an observer. 
</P>
