<HEADLINE> Albania Force Will Stick to Relief Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The work of the multinational
"Operation Alba (Dawn)" force in Albania will be limited to escort
tasks and the distribution of relief aid, the commander of the
force said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his first press conference, the Italian commander,
Lieutenant General Luciano Forlani, said the mission was to escort
and distribute relief aid provided by European governmental and
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said the multinational force would not deal with political
affairs or issues concerning the June parliamentary elections in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Forlani also stressed that his force would only deal with the
"recognized central and local authorities". He ruled out any
possible contacts with the local committees which emerged in the
south of the country during the anti-government protests in March.
</P>
<P>
Forlani said the situation in Albania was becoming better and
this would help the force carry out its mission.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council Resolution 1101 mandated
eight European countries to dispatch a 6,000-strong multinational
force to Albania on a three-month mission of humanitarian
relief. Since April 15, about 4,000 men of the force have been
stationed in the country. 
</P>
