<HEADLINE> Latin American Countries Congratulate Peru on Hostage Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUCRE, BOLIVIA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Latin American countries
today congratulated and supported Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori for ending the 126-day hostage siege in the Japanese
ambassador's residence in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers here reported that the presidents of Bolivia,
Ecuador, Colombia, Venezuela and Panama who were at the two-day
Andean Community summit here, issued separate statements on the
crisis which ended after Peruvian troops stormed the Japanese
ambassador's residence in Lima on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The troops freed 71 of the 72 hostages held by members of the
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement. One hostage died of a heart
attack. All members of the rebel group were killed in the assault.
</P>
<P>
Bolivian President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada admitted the raid
was risky, but said, "I am very happy over the result." Bolivia's
ambassador to Peru Jorge Gumucio was one of the hostages rescued
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian President Ernesto Perez said he was very pleased
that nearly all the hostages were released alive.  He hoped that
the resolution of the crisis would serve as an example for all
countries to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran President Fabrian Alarcon expressed his solidarity
with the people and president of Peru and said that terrorism in
all its forms should be eradicated throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
A report from Santiago quoted Chilean President Eduardo Frei as
saying today, "In this case, extreme measures had to be taken."
</P>
<P>
In a phone call to Fujimori, Frei also noted that uprooting
terrorism is a task that all Latin American countries must assume.
</P>
<P>
A report from Tegucigalpa quoted Honduran Foreign Minister
Delmer Urbizo Panting as saying today,"The Honduran government
feels very satisfied over the release of the 72 people held
hostage since December 17, 1996, because it was an humane act on
the part of President Fujimori."
</P>
<P>
With dialogue exhausted and after such a prolonged period of
captivity for the hostages, any solution to the crisis was to be
expected, Panting added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Peruvian president Fernando Belaunde Terry
today highlighted the success of hostage rescue, saying that Peru
had returned to tranquility with the ending of the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the fact that we hoped for an end without
bloodshed, it was not so. But one cannot ask for perfection in such
difficult circumstances as this one," he said in an interview with
a local radio station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
