<HEADLINE> Two Killed in Railway Station Blast in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Two people were killed and at
least seven others injured in an explosion at a railway station in
Russia's southern town of Armavir Wednesday night, media reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The powerful blast, which occurred at about 7 p.m. local time
(1500 GMT) near the ticket office, shattered all the windows and
doors of the station, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Police and troops sealed off the station and the track, and
rail traffic was halted.
</P>
<P>
The two deaths were identified as a woman and a man, and the
wounded were immediately rushed to hospital.
</P>
<P>
No one claimed responsibility for the blast, but the explosive
device may have been hidden in a passenger's bag at the ticket
office or in the waiting room, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Armavir, in the northern Caucasus Mountains, is about 320
kilometers from the separatist region of Chechnya, and the railway
line goes to the Chechen capital of Grozny. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
