<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia to Face WTO Panel over Car Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will soon face a panel
of judges at the World Trade Organization (WTO) over its national
car policy after Japan's decision last week to bring its
complaints to the organization at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Since Indonesia's national car policy was announced by the
government early last year, Japan, the United State and the
European Union have been consistently expressing their objection
to it.
</P>
<P>
Under the national car policy, domestic car-makers can enjoy
tax exemption on condition that they raise the local content ratio
in their cars up to 60 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
The tax breaks were granted solely to Pt. Timor Putra Nasional,
a company controlled by President Soeharto's youngest son Hutomo
Mandala Putra.
</P>
<P>
The company is now producing, albeit imported, the national car
called Timor.
</P>
<P>
Criticism of the car policy from Japan, the U.S. and the EU
intensified after Jakarta announced last October that Pt. Timor
Putra was allowed to import 45,000 units of the Timor car from
South Korea for a year until its factory was ready to produce this
year.
</P>
<P>
Pt. Timor Putra was exempted from paying import duties and
luxury taxes which normally add about 60 percent to the price of
other cars in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Japan's car makers have suffered heavy loses since the
implementation of Indonesia's national car policy as their
products have occupied more than 80 percent of Indonesia's auto
market.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Japan, which failed to persuade Indonesia to withdraw its
national car policy after several rounds of bilateral negotiations
since November 1996 under WTO supervision, finally asked the
Geneva-based WTO this month to form a panel to examine its dispute
with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government had hoped to avert a panel at the WTO
while remaining determined not to budge an inch from its position.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto said Monday that his country will continue
to produce the Timor car despite the fact that Japan has
officially brought its complaints to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Meordiono said Indonesia, now capable
of producing aircraft and ships, will go ahead with the national
car.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Trade and Industry Minister Tunky Ariwibowo said
that Indonesia had very strong arguments for its national car
policy, including WTO clauses related to infant industries and
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, as a developing nation, still had until the year
2000 to adjust its trade, industrial and economic policies,
including its car policy, to comply with WTO rules, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who left here for Tokyo Wednesday on a four-day
trade mission, stressed Tuesday that he was optimistic Indonesia's
national car program would be completed by 1999 when the car would
have a local parts content of 60 percent --a hurdle which allows
all autos similar tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
However, some automotive industry analysts here said that
Indonesia's chance to win at the WTO panel was slim as its
argument was "very weak" compared to Japan's.
</P>
<P>
Mari E. Pangestu, an economist, said she agreed Indonesia would
have a weak argument before a WTO panel. She recommended that
Jakarta offer compensation to Japan, the U.S. and the EU to avoid
a potentially damaging examination by a panel.
</P>
<P>
But Suhari Sargo, an automotive industry analyst, said Japan,
the EU and the U.S. would not abandon their challenge to
Indonesia's controversial car policy even if Jakarta gave them
compensation.
</P>
<P>
If Indonesia loses, countries affected by the policy may impose
penalties, including tariffs, on Indonesian products entering
their markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, there would be no immediate impact on
Indonesia's auto industry nor its economy in general.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Summit Talks Fruitful: Presidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Both visiting Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin hailed today
their official talks as "fruitful".
</P>
<P>
In their speeches at the banquet held by Yeltsin in honor of
Jiang, who arrived here Tuesday for a five-day state visit, the two
leaders pledged to strive for further development of the
Sino-Russian strategic coordination partnership of equality and
mutual confidence oriented toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and Yeltsin held official talks in the Kremlin this
morning, which, as Yeltsin said in his speech, has witnessed both
sides sharing identical positions on many issues.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the two sides are satisfied with the steady and
healthy development of the Sino-Russian partnership in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
They will keep promoting active cooperation in various
fields of bilateral relations and in international affairs in the
spirit of good-neighborliness and friendship, equality and mutual
trust, mutually beneficial cooperation and mutual development,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
On the multipolarization of the world, Yeltsin said that no
countries should seek any special status or sole leadership, and
both China and Russia are ready to conduct constructive
cooperation and promote the multipolarization process.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the two countries and peoples, while seeking
mutual development and prosperity, are willing to make
contribution to world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia, as two great nations in the world, are both
permanent members of the United Nations Security Council, and are
fully aware of their responsibilities for the international
community, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"We are both determined to make unremitting efforts for the
establishment of a new international order featuring peace,
stability, fairness and equity," Jiang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
