<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Russian Presidents Stress Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said
here today that regular meetings between high-ranking officials of
China and Russia are very important for the development of
Sino-Russian relations and their cooperation on international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks during his talks with his Russian
counterpart Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
A regular meeting mechanism of high-ranking officials of
China and Russia is now in place, Jiang said, and invited Yeltsin
to visit China. In reply, Yeltsin said he was happy to do it in
this Autumn, adding that Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin will
visit China in June.
</P>
<P>
Noting the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping's comment "putting
an end to the past and creating the future" on the Sino-Russian
relations in late 1980s, Jiang said,"we can now confident to
say that the two great countries and peoples have successfully
fulfilled the historic task."
</P>
<P>
"The Sino-Russian relations have already come out of the ups
and downs in history and embarked on a bright road toward the 21st
century of comprehensive development," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that in addition to high-ranking exchange visits,
the two sides should also increase contacts and exchanges between
the non-governmental organizations, local governments, parties,
armed forces and media.
</P>
<P>
Jiang described Yeltsin's recent suggestion of passing the
long-term Sino-Russian friendship to the younger generations as
foresighted.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident that the political, economic and
social grounds of the Sino-Russian relations is to be further
expanded and consolidated.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of border demarcation, Yeltsin said that with
joint efforts of the two sides, demarcation on more than 3,000
kilometers has been finished and the remaining problems should be
solved with the help of the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that as the two countries have an equal and
cooperative relationship, it will not be difficult to solve the
problems, adding that Russia is ready to do the job within this
year in accordance with agreement reached by the two sides, on the
basis of friendly consultation, mutual understanding and respect.
</P>
<P>
During the talks Jiang expressed appreciation for Russia's "One
China" policy and Yeltsin said that his country will continue to
stick to this position.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral economic and trade ties, Jiang said that he is
confident that the annual two-way trade volume will reach 20
billion U.S. dollars by the end of the century as long as both
sides fully tap their potentials.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between the two largest neighbors in the world
was about seven billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As a first step in this move, the two sides should strive to
increase the figure to eight to 10 billion U.S. dollars this year,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his confidence that the development of economic
and trade ties will keep pace with the development of the
bilateral political ties.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with Jiang, Yeltsin asked Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin to take measures to promote economic and trade links
and deal with existing problems.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that Russia is interested in China's experiences
in economic reforms and the two sides may expand exchanges in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
Noting the forthcoming signing of a five-nation agreement on
reduction of military forces in border areas between China,
Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, on Thursday, Jiang
said that the significant agreement will be a creative act in
handling Post-cold war state-to-state relations and ensuring
regional security.
</P>
<P>
"Such a concrete move embodies a brand-new sense and a
brand-new pattern of security that differs from the cold-war
mentality, and it will have a positive bearing on peace, security
and stability of the region as well as the world at large," Jiang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
