<HEADLINE> More Companies to Report on Chemical Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. experts are suggesting that
global warming may be to blamed for this year's severe floods of
the country.
</P>
<P>
While viewing flood-damaged Grand Forks, North Dakota,
President Clinton said he expanded an "early warning system" for
detecting toxic chemicals which will deteriorate the environment.
</P>
<P>
Under new rules in the decade-old "Community Right to Know"
program, seven additional industries and 6,100 new facilities will
be forced to disclose the levels of toxic chemicals they release,
according to reports by U.S. press here today.
</P>
<P>
The seven industries include metal and coal mining, electric
utilities, hazardous-waste treatment, petroleum bulk terminals,
chemical wholesalers and solvent recovery services.  
