<HEADLINE> UK's Major Appeals for Voter Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major,
boosted by the latest opinion polls of a narrowing gap with the
opposition party, appealed to voters to trust his six years of
experience in office.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal to you: don't let whatever doubts you may have had
about the Conservative Party in the past weigh with you when the
future of the United Kingdom may be at stake," he told a rally in
Aberdeen, Scotland just eight days before voters cast their
ballots on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Today's Guardian newspaper showed Labor's lead had dramatically
dropped from 14 to just five points, the lowest level for Labor in
opinion polls since November 1993. Its lead has been as high as 28
points in the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
The ICM poll showed 33 percent of voters backed Major as the
best prime minister, compared with Labor leader Tony Blair on 32.
The gap was 13 points in Blair's favor on April 2.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said the poll showed Major's tactic of focusing
on Europe was working despite splits in his own party over policy
on a single European currency.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Blair today also urged his supporters to step up
their efforts and not fall prey to complacency.
</P>
<P>
"Get rid of this Conservative government and get a Labor
government in its place. We can only do it if you are going to
come out and support us on May 1," he said at a campaign rally.
</P>
<P>
But a Gallup poll in today's Daily Telegraph put Labor 21
points ahead, an increase of five in a week. 
</P>
