<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banja Luka Airport Ready for Civil Traffic, SFOR Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The technical conditions for
civilian flights to and from the Banja Luka airport are now in
place, a Belgrade news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The news agency Beta quoted Robert Jordan, spokesman for
Nato-led Stablization Force (SFOR), as saying that the conditions
have been restored with the financial aid of 650,000 German marks
from the British government.
</P>
<P>
The money was used to buy computer equipment and repair runway
and airport lights in the airfield, which is near Banja Luka, the
second largest city in Bosnia and the principal town in the
Republica Srpska.
</P>
<P>
But in order to resume civilian traffic, agreement must be
reached between Bosnia's two entities, the RS and the Bosnian
Federation and the International Civic Aviation Organization must
give its permission, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
Civilian flights to the Banja Luka airport have been stopped
since May 31, 1992, when the war broke out in Bosnia. At the
moment, the Sarajevo airport is the only airhub of Bosnia open for
civilian traffic.
</P>
<P>
Nato Secretary General Javier Solana, during his visit here
last week, called on Bosnian parties to open more airports to
strengthen contacts with each other as well as to improve their
traffic abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
