<HEADLINE> Sterling Strength Hits Hard in Northern England </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The performance of northern
businesses fell sharply in the first quarter of 1997, with export
sales and order slipping to their lowest level since the third
quarter of 1992, according to the latest Business Survey North.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which forms part of the British Chambers of
Commerce national quarterly report, said the damage caused to the
UK's international price competitiveness by a strong pound appears
to be hitting northern companies hard.
</P>
<P>
Based on responses from 534 companies in north-east England and
Cumbria, the survey said businesses "came down to earth with a
bump", after record performances in the fourth quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and export sales, orders, and profits recorded
substantial falls, although the survey expressed optimism for
future profits.
</P>
<P>
Export sales fell, with a sharp drop in manufacturing exports
and a marginal decline in the service sector; overall the balance
was plus 11 in the first quarter of 1997, against plus 32 in the
fourth quarter of 1996. The overall balance for 1996 was plus 25.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of business bodies such as the CBI and the BCC can see
the problem sterling is creating for UK exporters, but they are
unsure about what, if any, moves to recommend to counter it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
