<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England, Wales Ahead of EU States in Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Crime in England and Wales has
risen at a faster rate than in any other European country during
the past decade, according to a report published today.
</P>
<P>
England and Wales are far ahead of their nearest fellow member
states in the crime boom sweeping the Continent.
</P>
<P>
An additional investigation carried out on behalf of the
European Commission found that new forms of hi-tech crime have
evolved into a thriving business rivaling the narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
The findings follow a year-long investigation by Deloitte and
Touche, the accountancy firm, which concludes that differences in
the laws of the European member states and the complete absence of
any effective judicial co-operation allow international fraud to
prosper.
</P>
<P>
England and Wales come top out of 10 countries, far ahead of
nations such as France, the Netherlands, Greece, and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Scotland has the lowest recorded increase among the 10
countries.
</P>
<P>
In the nine-year period to 1995 the number of crimes recorded
in England and Wales rose by 31 percent to 5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
Dr Roger Matthews, Reader in Criminology at Middlesex
University, said: "Particularly bad news for England and Wales is
that not only have we experienced the highest increase in recorded
crime over the nine-year period but that this increase has been
associated with an increase in violent and serious crime."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
