<HEADLINE> Grand Jury Indicts Teenagers in Hate Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A grand jury Wednesday
indicted three Chicago white teenagers in the apparent hate crime
beating of a 13-year-old black youth.
</P>
<P>
The teens, who remain free on bond, were charged last month by
the Cook County state's attorney. When they appeared in court
Wednesday for a preliminary hearing, however, they were told
prosecutors had superseded, or replaced, the original charges with
a grand jury indictment, the United Press International reported.
</P>
<P>
The three teenagers, age 18, 17 and 19, are charged with
attempted murder, aggravated battery and committing a hate crime
in a savage attack in Armour Square Park that left Lenard Clark in
a coma for days.
</P>
<P>
The teenagers will be back in court May 8th, when they are
expected to plead not guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
Clark, an 8th grader, and two other boys were riding their
bicycles in the mostly white working-class enclave of Bridgeport
last month when the teens allegedly attacked Clark, shouting
racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
Clark was thrown into a cement wall, kicked and suffered brain
damage. He is undergoing therapy at the Rehabilitation Institute
of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
The beating has prompted concern about racial tensions in the
South Side neighborhood and the city in general. Politicians,
activists and religious leaders have denounced the beating,
calling for greater tolerance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
