<HEADLINE> UN to Hold Emergency Special Session on Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The UN General Assembly
will meet in a emergency special session on Israeli-Palestinian
issue on Thursday following the request of Arab countries and
consent of majority of member states, a UN spokeswoman announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the news briefing, spokeswoman Samsiah Abdul-Majid
noted that as of this morning there were 40 speakers inscribed for
the special session.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations had held nine emergency special sessions
before. The first one was convened on the question of Suez Canal
in 1956 and the last one on the question of the Golan Heights
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council had failed twice to adopt a resolution on
ending Israeli settlement in east Jerusalem and other occupied
territories on March 7 and March 21 because of U.S. vetos.
</P>
<P>
Arab states had submitted a request to UN secretary-general for
an emergency special session of the General Assembly on March 30
to consider the situation in the Middle East and recommend the
necessary measures to end Israel's illegal actions and save the
peace process. 
</P>
