<HEADLINE> US Senate Debates Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today began
its debate on the Chemical Weapons Convention as Republican Bob
Dole, once a leading opponent of the treaty, expressed his support
for the convention.
</P>
<P>
The Senate will vote on several amendments called as "killer"
to the treaty by the administration before voting on the pact on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Making last attempt for the approval before the vote, U.S.
President Bill Clinton today invited his former presidential
election rival Dole to the White House.
</P>
<P>
Standing shoulder-to-shoulder with Clinton, Dole, expressing
his satisfaction with clarifications agreed on by the
administration, urged the Senate to pass the convention.
</P>
<P>
"Is it perfect? No. But I believe there are now adequate
safeguards to protect American interests," Dole said.
</P>
<P>
"If I were present in the Senate, I would vote for the CWC
because of the many improvements that have been agreed to," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The event in the White House today also gathered retired
General Colin Powell and other prominent Republican figures who
support the convention.
</P>
<P>
However, when opening the Senate debate today, Jesse Helms,
Chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, reiterated his
opposition to the treaty, declaring it "is worse than nothing".
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Article 10 and Article 11 of the convention
should be modified before the Senate approves the treaty, saying
the provisions would allow so-called "rogue states" to obtain
chemical weapons technology.
</P>
<P>
Despite the strong opposition, supporters believe that they
would get a two-thirds majority for approval of the treaty in
Thursday's vote.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which was signed in 1993 and has been ratified by
74 countries, is to take effect on April 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
