<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Senate Back NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today urged senators to support the expansion
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
She told the Senate Armed Service Committee that the expansion
of the alliance would benefit the U.S. and ensure peace and
security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the committee together with Defense Secretary
William Cohen, Albright said that she would visit Russia next week
to try to work out differences on a proposed agreement between
Russia and the Atlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
She ruled out the possibility that the alliance would make
concessions in negotiations between NATO and Russia, concerning
the deployment of combat forces and nuclear weapons on the
territories of the new members.
</P>
<P>
Russia would like the alliance to "make absolute commitments"
in the document not to deploy nuclear and conventional forces in
the new members after NATO expanded.
</P>
<P>
"But we will not compromise on this issue," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to be going to Moscow to have some additional
meetings on the subject, probably next week, because there are
elements of the agreement not decided upon," she said.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin declared last week in Germany
that Moscow and Russia will sign the document on May 27 in Paris.
But Washington said later that the date for the signing is yet to
be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that she hoped the alliance will sign the
document to create a formal security cooperation mechanism with
Russia on May 27, but stressing there is still no agreement so
far.
</P>
<P>
She did not give an exact date for her trip to Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
