<HEADLINE> EC Examines Economic Situation of EU Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC),
the European Union (EU)'s executive body, today examined the
economic situation of EU countries in the light of the Spring
economic forecasts of the Commission's services.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts were presented Wednesday in Brussels by
Yves-Thibault de Silguy, EU commissioner responsible for economic,
financial and monetary affairs.
</P>
<P>
The EC welcomed the continued progress by EU member nations
towards meeting the convergence criteria and the good prospects
for a majority of countries to be ready to participate in monetary
union from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the improvements in GDP growth projected in the
EC's previous forecasts appear to be on track, bolstered by low
interest rates, the recent return of the dollar to more realistic
levels, strong external demand, favorable wage developments and
continued low inflation.
</P>
<P>
Stronger growth will help EU member states with their ambitious
efforts to control public finances and contribute to reducing
unemployment, which remains the first economic policy priority for
the EU, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The EC reportedly has agreed its recommendation for the broad
economic policy guidelines which will be approved by the European
Council in Amsterdam. It also agreed draft recommendations to the
Council concerning the remaining 10 countries with excessive
deficits.
</P>
<P>
The EC has recommended that the Netherlands and Finland be
removed from the list of countries with an excessive budget deficit.
</P>
