<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Debt Relief of $338 Mln for Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of a debt relief package that will reduce Uganda's
debt by 338 million U.S. dollars in Net Present Value (NPV) terms,
of which 160 million dollars will be provided by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
In a news release, the World Bank explained that in nominal
terms the value of this package could be in excess of 700 million
dollars, with the Bank's own contribution estimated at 430 million
dollars, also in nominal terms.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the package, the International Development
Association (IDA), the concessionary lending wing of the World
Bank for developing nations, will provide some 75 million dollars
in the form of grants during the 12-month period between the
decision point of April 1997 and completion point of April 1998.
Other creditors will contribute their share of the relief.
</P>
<P>
The package, to be delivered by April 1998, will reduce
Uganda's debt to a sustainable level that will enable the country
to exit from the debt rescheduling process.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern African country is the first one to benefit under
the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Debt Initiative.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the announcement, Ugandan Minister of Planning
and Economic Development, Richard Kaijuka who is on a visit to
Washington D.C., noted:"It is very good news for all Ugandans. We
hope that all multilaterals and bilaterals join this initiative,
which gives new hope to Sub-Saharan Africa." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
