<HEADLINE> China, Germany Begin Talks on High-Tech Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China and Germany launched here
today a dialogue forum to promote bilateral high-tech cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the forum began today in Bonn and will
last through Friday.
</P>
<P>
The forum, known as the Chinese-German Dialogue Forum for
High-Technology, was initiated by Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulation message to the event, Chinese Premier Li
Peng said that the forum would not only boost high-tech policy
exchange between the two governments, but also provide a venue for
research institutes and enterprises from both sides to explore
high-tech cooperation projects and their commercialization.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also sent a message to the meeting, saying that the goal
of the forum is to identify concrete and commercially applicable
projects which benefit both sides.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the confidence that the forum will serve as a
good basis for further development of the relations between
Germany and China.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jinhua, chief of China's state planning commission, heads
the Chinese delegation at the talks, while Germany is represented
by economics minister Guenter Rexrodt and research minister
Juergen Ruettgers.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from both countries also include industrialists and
representatives from leading research institutes.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese officials, the talks in Bonn will mainly
explore possible joint projects in fields such as electronics,
coal processing, chemical production and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Germany is China's biggest trade partner in Europe. According
to statistics of the Chinese Customhouse, trade between the two
countries reached 13.17 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued today by German Economics Ministry said
German direct investment in China is expected to rise from the
present level of 1.5 billion marks (877 million US dollars) to
between four and five billion marks (between 2.3 and 2.9 billion
dollars) in the coming few years.
</P>
<P>
The German investment will be mainly channeled into such areas
as energy, automotive plants and petrochemical production, the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
