<HEADLINE> Worldwide Printer Market to Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide market for
computer printers will grow to 76.5 million units in 2001, up 77
percent from 43.3 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a new report by the International Data Corp.,
manufacturers such as Fujitsu of Japan and Hewlett-Packard of the
United States are expected to introduce printers with the same
printing speed but cheaper than existing models later this year.
</P>
<P>
On the U.S. market, the ink-jet color printers of Canon and HP
are enjoying a fastly growing share. Its energy saving and
moderate price setting characteristics have attracted a great deal
of customers. Most of such color printers have a resolution no
less than 300 dots per inch (DPI).
</P>
<P>
Laser printers get even higher resolution, up to 600 DPI, whose
prices are also going down and speed is going up.
</P>
<P>
Experts also said that wide-range application of multimedia
computers has offered more opportunities for printer makers.
</P>
<P>
Market observers said that the prices of ink-jet printers have
declined by almost a third over the past two years. Those of laser
printers have dropped by at least a quarter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the market saw a fast selling of peripheral gadgets
of printers, including mostly ink and drums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Launches Slovak Koruna Bond Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the launching of a Slovak Koruna
bond issue for the amount of SKK 1.0 billion (some 30 million U.S.
dollars) under its Global Medium Term Note program.
</P>
<P>
This is the IFC's second issue in the Euro Slovak Koruna
market.
</P>
<P>
The one-year notes carry an annual coupon of 13.625 percent and
were re-offered at a price of 100.000 percent. The proceeds of the
issue will be swapped into U.S. dollars floating-rate funds.
</P>
<P>
The transaction brings the IFC's market borrowings to about 3.7
billion dollars for the fiscal year 1997, which began on July 1,
1996.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
multilateral source of lending for private sector projects in
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 414 Mln Dlr Stand-By Credit for Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today announced the approvement of a 13-month stand-by
credit for Romania, equivalent to some 414 million U.S. dollars,
in a bid to support the government's 1997-98 economic program.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, about 83 million dollars is available
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The economic program for 1997-98 seeks a decline in the
external current account deficit to 4.5 percent of GDP in 1997
from 6.6 percent last year, and a sharp cut in the monthly rate of
inflation to about 2 percent by the end of 1997, from a monthly
rate of 10 percent at end-1996. However, real GDP growth is
expected to decline by 1.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Romania joined the IMF in December 1972. Its quota is about
1,035 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit
currently totals some 581 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
