<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Hails Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar Hassan
al-Bashir reaffirmed here today that the signing of the peace
agreement between his government and four southern rebel factions
constitutes a positive solution to the 14-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Monday agreement defined a four-year transition period,
during which a coordination council composed of government
officials and representatives of the four factions will take
charge of affairs in the south.
</P>
<P>
The largest anti-government group operating in southern Sudan,
the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) didn't sign the
accord.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference today, al-Bashir said that the
devastating war in southern Sudan has given rise to numerous
economic, political and social problems.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, after the transition period,
citizens in the south will decide by ballot whether they will stay
in or to separate form the country.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir expressed his hope that a successful implementation
of the agreement would lead to the unity of Sudan through a
nation-wide plebiscite after the transition period.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir pointed out that the agreement faces many challenges,
including the one posed by John Garang, the leader of the SPLA.
</P>
<P>
Another challenge facing the agreement, said the president, is
the resettlement of refugees as well as the issue of
reconstruction and development.
</P>
<P>
The government is keen on implementing huge development
projects in the southern area with a view to affording job
opportunities to those who surrendered to the government after the
signing of the peace agreement, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Refuses to Fully Lift Ban on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The government of Tanzania
today stressed that the eased sanctions against Burundi are still
for only humanitarian items as it was decided during the last
Arusha summit on April 16.
</P>
<P>
Principal Secretary in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
International Co-operation, Ally Mtango, told a press conference
here today that the rest of the sanctions are there to stay.
</P>
<P>
Mtango refuted press reports in a neighboring country that the
Burundian military government headed by Major Pierre Buyoya had
been authorized to enter into negotiations with the
sanctions-imposing African countries geared towards the lifting
of sanctions on the remaining items including oil products.
</P>
<P>
He said the Burundian leader's request to have the sanctions
on fuel lifted was categorically refused by the regional leaders
when they briefed him on decisions made during the summit.
</P>
<P>
"No negotiations will therefore be undertaken with individual
governments on lifting the remaining sanctions as claimed in the
article which quoted Jean Luo Ndizeye, a spokesman of the
Burundian leader," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The principal secretary further said the sanctions are
affecting not only Burundi but also Tanzania, adding that the
later loses two million U.S. Dollars per month in revenue.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very big blow. But it is the contribution of the
people of Tanzania towards solving the crisis in Burundi," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Mtango also refuted allegations that the regional as well as
national sanctions co-ordinating committee had been dissolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
