<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges Moi to Continue With Peace Effort in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today implored visiting Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
to continue his efforts to bring peace to Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists after holding two-hour official talks
with Moi, Mugabe said they had discussed the Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We must never tire, we must never accept 'no' for an answer
in our efforts to have them (Zaire President Mobutu Sese Seko and
rebel leader Laurent Kabila) meet. Really, Zaire has a peace
program. So I have been urging President Moi not to tire," said
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations on Monday urged Mobutu and Kabila to hold
talks in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, Kabila has so far been insisting that any talks
should center on the aspect of Mobutu handing over power, while
Mobutu failed to produce a response, citing poor health.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for us to maintain a peaceful environment,
and also to do our best to bring peace to Zaire," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed bilateral relations,
cooperation and friendship which they said should continue to be
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Moi, who arrived here today on his first four-day state visit
to Zimbabwe, will officially open the Zimbabwe International
Trade Fair '97 in the second city Bulawayo on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
