<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 32 Private Health Facilities Registered in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 32 private health
facilities, including dispensaries, health centers, hospitals,
dental and medical clinics, have been registered so far under the
new guideline standards for health facilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Registrar of private hospitals at the Ministry of Health,
Henock Ngonyani, told a press conference here today that the
Private Hospitals Advisory Board has to date scrutinized 44
applications.
</P>
<P>
"Out of the 44 applications, 20 have been accepted without
conditions while 12 have been accepted but with conditions. We
never approved the other 12 applications because they never met
the guideline standards," Ngonyani said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry suspended registration of private health
facilities last November, directing all private practitioners to
re-apply for registration under the new guideline standards before
June this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Ngonyani, the new guideline standards are aimed
at maintaining good quality, effective and efficient health
services delivery in Tanzania mainland.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania mainland had a total of 1,531 private health
facilities, most of which have been operating under
unsatisfactory standards, raising concern of the ministry of
health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Bank Workers on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Workers at Standard Chartered
Bank, Zimbabwe's largest commercial bank, went on strike today,
demanding better working conditions and autonomy in the
management of the bank's local operations.
</P>
<P>
The bank controls over 50 percent of the country's financial
market, which means the strike has affected a lot of workers
whose salaries come through the bank.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which has paralyzed most of the bank's activities
in major urban centers, saw nearly 95 percent of the bank's
non-managerial staff participating, resulting in only five
branches offering limited service in capital Harare.
</P>
<P>
The workers, who vowed not to return to work until their
grievances are resolved, accused the bank's management of
frustrating their attempts to resolve the problems of
profit-sharing and performance appraisals, which have been
dragging on since 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
