<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Economy Ranks First in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's economy has
become the strongest in the gulf region as the Gross Domestic
Product reached 136 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Minister of National Economy and Finance Ibrahim Bin Abdul
Aziz Al-Assaf was quoted by the Saudi Press Agency as saying today
that the 1996 GDP, an 8.8 percent rise over that of 1995, puts the
country's economy at the 28th in position worldwide.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the achievement to a stable economic policy, the
free market economy and the appropriate conditions for local and
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
A good performance was also reported in the balance of
payments in 1996, with a total of 186 million U.S. dollars surplus
in the current accounts, compared with a deficit of a 5.3 billion
dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus was mainly due to higher oil prices in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil is Saudi Arabia's main export item. Its current
output quota assigned by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) is 8 million barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
Despite lower petrochemical prices in 1996, as well as lower
agricultural exports, the Ministry of Finance and National
Economy said 1996's overall non-oil exports rose about 2.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The oil price hike helped increase the kingdom's revenues in
1996 by 11 billion U.S. dollars, which allowed the government to
raise the budget spendings from 40 billion dollars to 51.7 billion
dollars, with an actual deficit of 4.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total imports last year declined by 1.5 percent
to 25.2 billion dollars from 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
