<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Chief Upholds Arab, Islamic Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) Izzidine Laraki today
expressed the OIC's support for Arab and Islamic efforts to push
ahead the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Laraki, who arrived here on Monday, held talks today with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the Palestinian cause,
Jerusalem and perils threatening the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following this meeting, Laraki said the Islamic states support
the rights of the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon and uphold the
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He said the peace process should be based on agreements
concluded by the Palestinians and Israelis as well as on the
Palestinian rights to establish their own state, with Jerusalem
as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The OIC chief pointed out that his organization has adopted
several resolutions recently that are aimed at forcing Israel to
implement international resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The 52-member OIC has called for Islamic countries to
reconsider ties with Israel at its March summit meeting in
Islamabad, Pakistan, in light of Israel's settlement activities
in Jerusalem, a city holy to Muslims, Christians and Jews alike.
</P>
<P>
A special OIC Jerusalem Committee held in Rabat, Morocco, also
condemned the Israeli decision to build new Jewish settlement in
disputed East Jerusalem, a move that has stalled the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The OIC believes in abidance by signed treaties and
commitment to international legitimacy taking into consideration
the fact that Israel was the primary beneficiary of the peace
process," he added.
</P>
<P>
He termed as "a great idea," the initiative by King Hassan II
of Morocco to establish a fund for supporting Jerusalem, during
the Jerusalem Committee meeting in Rabat in March.
</P>
<P>
The statutes of the fund have already been devised and it has
been agreed that the fund will be a free foundation raising money
for the sake of Jerusalem, said the OIC chief.
</P>
<P>
"It is an important step to fight Israel's Judaization
operations," he said, adding that a meeting will be held soon to
discuss the fund's program of action.
</P>
<P>
Laraki said that the OIC should be a tool to serve Islamic
causes and its members politically and economically.
</P>
<P>
Laraki arrived here Monday at the start of his four-nation
tour designed to show solidarity with the Arab and Islamic
countries' stance on the Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
The visit is the first of its kind paid by Laraki since he
became new OIC chief early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
