<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yang Ying, the One to Watch in Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Yang Ying, one of
the youngest players on the Chinese national table tennis team,
will use the oldest weapon in the Chinese arsenal to shoot at
glory in the World Table Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Yang, who plays table tennis in Chinese
traditional penhold grip, the style once branded as outdated as
the wooden tennis racket and scissor-style high jump, never
admits her style is now ineffective in the era of speed and spin.
</P>
<P>
"I will vindicate the Chinese traditional way of playing table
tennis in this championships," said Yang, who along with world
No. 1 Deng Yaping will lead the Chinese team's bid for their 12th
Corbillion Cup in the Manchester Worlds which kicks off Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Yang, the world best women penholder, said the handshaker did
have an advantage over penholder in the covering of table, but
the latter was faster and better at placement shots.
</P>
<P>
The handshake and penhold styles play as their names suggest.
A handshaker grips the racket as if he or she is shaking
someone's hand and uses one side of the racket for forehands and
the other for backhands.
</P>
<P>
Traditional penholder like world No. 4 Yang uses only one side
of the racket for both strokes and grips the racket like holding
a pen.
</P>
<P>
The handshake style allows players to attack easily with
topspins or flat shots from both wings of the table but is prone
to leave an opening in the middle of the table. The penhold
grip, on the other hand, is well suited for flat forehands and
defensive dropshots but is short on backhand power.
</P>
<P>
Unlike China's Olympic champion Liu Guoliang, who sticks
rubber onto both sides of the racket and plays topspins with
backhand, Yang is a die-hard traditionalist.
</P>
<P>
"I won't stick rubber onto the reverse side of the racket, a
heavier racket will make me difficult to handle placement shots,"
Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the old style, Yang is the one to watch at the world
championships.
</P>
<P>
She is only second to Deng Yaping in the Chinese team and has
been combining with world No. 1 Deng at the women's doubles event
since Deng's longtime partner Qiao Hong retired from national
service to join a Japanese club last year.
</P>
<P>
Yang and Deng, who have swept the doubles titles at the French
Open, Swedish Open and Grand Prix Finals, are odds-on favorites
in doubles in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
Yang is expected to win a singles medal if she doesn't meet
her doubles partner in early rounds.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who has brought as much fame as shame to the player five
years her junior, seems a summit insurmountable for Yang.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who lifted the eyebrows of pundits as she upset Deng in
the 1991 national championships, has never got the better of her
teammate since.
</P>
<P>
"Yaping has stronger mentality and more experience than me,"
Yang admits.
</P>
<P>
Yang denied the idea that living in the era of Deng Yaping was
a misfortune.
</P>
<P>
"The opposite is right," she said. "I have learned a lot from
Yaping. She teaches me how to toughen my nerves and improve my
skills." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Tao Chases Elusive Singles Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 23 (Xinhua) -- It may be Wang Tao's
last shot at a major singles title before his retirement and he
promises he won't let the chance slip easily this time.
</P>
<P>
"I really want to wrap up my career with a singles
championship," said the Chinese table tennis veteran, who had held
the men's world top ranking for a brief time and is currently
rated sixth.
</P>
<P>
Wang, 29, the oldest player on the Chinese lineup for the 44th
World Table Tennis Championships, has proven that he is more than
a doubles expert with impressive singles performances for a decade.
</P>
<P>
The stocky lefthander, who won the decider against Jorgen
Persson in China's 3-2 victory over Sweden in the 1995
championships team final and had also comepted in the 1993 final,
has never won a singles title in the Olympics, world championships
or World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Wang jumped to international stardom as he partnered Liu Wei to
win the mixed doubles event in the 1991 world championships, where
he also combined with Lu Lin to finish runners-up in the men's
doubles.
</P>
<P>
Wang swept the doubles and mixed doubles titles in the 1993
world championships, nine months after taking an Olympic gold
medal in doubles at Barcelona. In the 1995 championships, Wang
once again grabbed two doubles titles.
</P>
<P>
Major singles title has twice been within easy reach of Wang,
but he suqandered both chances -- the first, to lack of
motivation, and the second, to over-confidence.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Taek Soo, who had never got the advantage of
Wang, upset the Chinese in the quarter-finals at the 1995
championships.
</P>
<P>
Kim was later thrown out of the championships after his bat was
detected to have been applied with a speed-and-spin enhancing glue
banned by the International Table Tennis Federation. Wang
retained the semi-final spot to take on fellow Chinese Liu
Guoliang.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who inisisted he had lost his quarter-final match against
Kim, looked lackluster in the semi-finals and sent Liu into the
final.
</P>
<P>
In the Atlanta Olympics, Wang overcame Czech giant-killer Petr
Kobbel and Belarus' rising star Vladimir Samsonov to join Liu in
the final.
</P>
<P>
Having won most of his encounters with Liu since the 1995
championships, Wang lost his vigilance and got a battering from
the teammate nine years his junior.
</P>
<P>
"I have won most of my matches against Liu for a year, he has
never played so well," shell-shocked Wang lamented after the loss.
</P>
<P>
Playing an aggressive game close to table, Wang has been tipped
as a singles title hopeful for the last two world championships.
This time, he still is.
</P>
<P>
"Wang Tao is one of the greatest players in the world and he
has ability and mentality to be a champion," said Kim Taek Soo.
</P>
<P>
Born in a family of avid table tennis fans in Beijing, Wang
took a zigzag road to international fame. After the Beijing team
slammed the door to Wang because of his short figure, he took a
70-hour-long train journey alone to a team in Northwest China's
Xinjiang when he was 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
Wang joined the Chinese Army team several years later and now
holds a ranking of colonel.
</P>
<P>
Wang is still smart over the refusal by the Beijing team.
"They didn't want me because they thought I had no potential," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
