<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Landmine Symposium Ends in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) --Senior diplomats and defence
officials from the southern African countries today backed UN
resolutions calling for a total ban on anti-personnel mines, which
they said must be implemented urgently throughout the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
The officials from the 12 Southern African Development Community
(SADC) nations, who held a three-day smposium on landmines in harare,
agreed that those who have used and those who have supplied
anti-personnel mines which kill and injure some 2,000 people per
month worldwide, bear a joint responsibility to ensure the clearance
of these lethal weapons and the provision of adequate care to the
victims.
</P>
<P>
''Since 1,100 years will be required at the current rate to clear
the world of mines currently in the ground, parties to conflicts
should not add to this burden through new deployments of
anti-personnel mines,'' said a three-page declaration endorsed by
about 100 participants to the symposium organised by the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) and sponsored by the
Organisation of African Unity and the Zimbabwe government.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 20 million mines, or a fifth of those in the world,
are on southern African soil, representing a direct threat to the
health, welfare and survival of many millions of people in the region
and a major obstacle to post-conflict reconstruction and development.
</P>
<P>
According to the ICRC, the total known figure of landmines
throughout the world as at January this year was 113 million with
Egypt leading with a record 23 million mines followed by Iran with 16
million and Angola with 15 million mines.
</P>
<P>
Other countries in Africa most affected by mines are Mozambique
with three million, Zimbabwe with two million, Eritrea, Sudan,
Somalia with one million each and Ethiopia with half a million.
</P>
<P>
The participants voiced concern that landmines indiscriminately
kill and maim civilians and combatants alike and continued to do so
long after conflicts end.
</P>
<P>
They called on SADC states to launch an initiative for the
establishment of a regional zone free of anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to promote the strongest possible resolution on
anti-personnel mines at the forthcoming June summit of the OAU in
Harare. enditem

=04231707

=04231714
NNNN
01:13 01:14 g # PAB
</P>
