<HEADLINE> Kenya, Ethiopia Issue Joint Communique on Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Ethiopia today
reaffirmed their firm commitment to the maintenance of peace in
the common border areas, according to a Kenya News Agency report
today.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued today in Embu, northern Kenya, said
that the Ethiopian government agreed to pressurize the culprits
of the border incursion in Kenya to return all livestock,
firearms and police uniforms stolen from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The communique signed by both governments' representatives at
the end of three-day border talks noted that elders and officials
from the two countries would meet again in June this year in
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the June meeting is designed to
discuss outstanding issues pertaining to the compensation of
losses of life and property.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that more regular meetings in the event of
insecurity incidents along common border should be held due to
poor communication between border officials of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the issues of cattle rustling raised by the
Ethiopian delegation, the Kenyan delegation promised to
investigate and take appropriate action.
</P>
<P>
The second round of the border talks was held to discuss last
month's border attacks on Marsabit District in Kenya by armed
gangsters from the Ethiopian side.
</P>
<P>
During the attacks, about 80 people, including 17 Kenyan
security officers and 16 armed bandits, were killed when Shangilla
and Armakolle bandits attacked the area bordering Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, a Kenyan delegation visited Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia, and held talks with a Ethiopian delegation on the
border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
