<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Re-conditions Progress in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Emerging intact from the
Bar-On scandal, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu today
reaffirmed that the progress on the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process was conditional on the Palestinian commitment to
combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu convened at his office a special meeting of the
Knesset (Israeli Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee
to review the current state of the peace process and Israel's
security situation.
</P>
<P>
Blaming Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser
Arafat for "dragging his feet in the campaign against terrorism,"
Netanyahu said the security cooperation between Israeli and
Palestinian security forces was now at a very low and limited
level.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel was still in danger of what he termed as
terrorism, although there was no concrete warnings of new
extremist attacks at present. He stressed that unless Arafat
changed his attitude towards fighting terrorism, the peace
process could not advance.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier revealed that the United States was
formulating a new proposal on advancing the peace process, which
is based on the idea of accelerating the final-status talks. But
he did not go into details.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time Netanyahu touched on the peace
process following the Bar-On scandal, which created a crisis of
survival for him in the past week after the police recommended
indicting him for his involvement in the affair. However, the
state prosecution announced Sunday to drop the indictment against
him because of the lack of sufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
Signs have shown that the Bar-On scandal could have negative
implications on the peace process. In his comments on the
prosecution's decision Sunday evening, Netanyahu blasted the
leftist camp for launching an illegitimate campaign against him
in the Bar-On affair.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had been charged with involvement in the short-lived
appointment of former Jerusalem Mayor Roni Bar-On as the
attorney-general in January.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his resolve to continue his hardline policies,
including the building of the Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem, opposing the division of Jerusalem, rejecting the
establishment of a Palestinian state and refusing to return the
Golan Heights to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Following the Bar-On scandal for which Netanyahu was harshly
criticized by other ministers for shutting them out in the
decision-making process, he is expected to increase consultations
within the cabinet in making decisions.
</P>
<P>
This means Netanyahu has become more vulnerable to the
pressure from the hardliners within his government, thus making
it more difficult for him to make concessions to the Palestinian
side, observers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970424.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN-OAU Envoy Arrives in Luanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- UN-OAV Envoy to the Great Lakes
Region Mohammed Sahnoun arrived here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He will meet Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos on the
Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
