<HEADLINE> NATO Military Chiefs Broadly Agree on Command </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO's military chiefs have
achieved broad agreement Tuesday on the radical changes of NATO's
command structure designed to bring it into line with the
realities of the post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
General Klaus Naumann, chairman of NATO's Military Committee,
told a news conference today, after a meeting of the chiefs of
defense staff of the 16 NATO allies with their counterparts from
NATO's 27 partner countries, that NATO's military chiefs had
achieved agreement Tuesday on most of the issues concerning
restructuring of NATO's command structure.
</P>
<P>
He said that the agreed package would move the alliance from 65
headquarters at four command levels to 20 at three levels.
</P>
<P>
According to the German general, it was also agreed at the
meeting that the current three regional commands in Europe would
be cut to two (northern and southern commands), scrapping the
current central command, based in Britain.
</P>
<P>
He said that the package would now be submitted to the North
Atlantic Council, NATO's highest decision-making body, for
approval.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the arrangement of sub-regional commands in
the southern European flank had yet to be solved.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Britain, supported by Canada, was pushing
for a package of financial and manpower limits in exchange for
losing a prestigious regional command.
</P>
<P>
In the south, Greece, Turkey, Italy, Spain and Portugal all
want a command on their territory.
 01:27CAB069i0423ql01:4201:431260
</P>
<P>
General Naumann also told reporters that NATO military chiefs
had fully agreement on the implementation of the Combined Joint
Task Forces (CJTF), including a CJTF headquarters concept and
conducting two exercises, one in autumn and the other in the
spring of 1998, to test the concept.
</P>
<P>
The CJTF concept, which was endorsed by foreign ministers from
NATO member states last June in Berlin, will enable NATO's
European nations to conduct their own operations, like
peacekeeping missions, using NATO assets.
</P>
<P>
General Naumann said that the France-US dispute concerning who
would run the Nepals-based southern command in Europe had not
been discussed at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The post in southern Europe is traditionally held by an
American general and is demanded by France to be handed over to an
European, in order to make the European Security and Defense
Identity "more visible."
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, both NATO and the partner countries
expressed their desire to further enhance the Partnership for
Peace program and to get partner countries more involved in NATO's
planning for Partnership for Peace activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
