<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Arab Joint Effort to Advance Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister
Jawad Anani today stressed the importance of continuing
coordination among Arab countries to save the floundering Mideast
peace process, when recent diplomatic efforts seem to have failed.
</P>
<P>
Anani said that Arab countries should intensify their
coordination in order to protect Arab and Palestinian rights and
fight the Israeli settlement schemes.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Voice of Arab radio, Anani
stressed Jordan's refusal of "all Israeli attempts to Judaize
Jerusalem," which Israel seized in 1967 and later annexed.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to mediate between the Israelis and the
Palestinians and coordinate stands with all Arab brothers,
especially Egypt," the Jordanian official added.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan played a key role in January in a deal
on the Israeli partial redeployment in Hebron. But the situation
went worse afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat flew to the Red Sea resort of Aqaba in Jordan for
talks with the Jordanian king on restarting the stalled Mideast
peace talks. He later returned home without making any statement.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have deadlocked for over a
month since Israel began construction of 6,500 homes for Jews in
disputed East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Hussein summit today came amid intensified Arab
diplomatic moves to bring the peace process back to track. Last
week Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak sent his political advisor
to the U.S. for consultations with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
However, the Mideast peace process has made no headway despite
all the efforts, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa noted today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri expressed
the hope that Israel "would return to the road of peace." 
</P>
