<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Launches Mass Arrests in Oil City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The police in Warri, the oil town
in southern Nigeria, embarked on mass arrests of people along the
streets Tuesday following the kidnaping of a policeman and the
death of five persons in clashes between armed youths and police.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports today, 13 other persons critically
wounded in the shoot-out are on admission at a private hospital
in the town.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the police launched a counter-attack
apparently for self-defence against the mob since the communal
clashes broke out a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The police has confirmed the incident, saying they are
screening those arrested so that innocent persons would not
suffer. But the police did not disclose how many people have been
detained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shell Petroleum Development Company operating in
the area said its crude oil production was going on normally.
</P>
<P>
The company said in a statement that the crisis in Warri
caused the shut-down of only one station and that its loss
amounted to just 2,000 barrels out of the total daily output of
950,000 barrels. 
</P>
