<HEADLINE> 30th Meeting of WTO Commission for Africa Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The 30th meeting of World
Tourism Organization (WTO) Regional Commission for Africa opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Ethiopian President Negasso Gidada
stressed the importance to create peace environment and fully use
Africa's potential to develop tourism.
</P>
<P>
He said, in 1996 while global tourism receipts reached 425
billion US dollars, Africa's share was only 8 billion US dollars,
representing only 1.8 percent of the global receipts.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, WTO Secretary General Francesco
Frangialli said in 1996 the world tourism set new records in terms
of both international tourist arrivals and tourism receipts.
</P>
<P>
He said, Africa also recorded a 7 percent increase in arrivals
in 1996 which ammounted to 20.6 million, whereas receipts rose more
steeply.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that Africa received only 3.5 percent
of world tourist flows and its receipts accounted for only 1.8
percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
In her address, Chairman of the WTO Commission for Africa
Vida Yeboah pointed out that Africa's position vis-a-vis the issue
of tourism is indeed a very baffling one.
</P>
<P>
''Very simply put: we need money, and the products that we have to
offer to the international traveller are bountiful and varied= with
careful planning and packaging of the tourism offerings, most of our
countries could attract much foreign receipts from tourism, but like
in most other areas this achievement seem to elude us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
She called for peace on the continent, saying that ''let internal
and external strife and violence cease and let us build together our
respective countries and maintain our God-given natural endowments
and our hard-won heritage for the improvement of the quality of life
of our peoples now, and most especially, for posterity.''
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of Ethiopian Tourism Commission Yusuf Abdullahi
Sukkar said on the occasion that Ethiopia has now once again created
an enabling environment for the development of its tourism sector.
''Consistent with its new liberalized economic policy, it has
formulated a strategy for the sector which encourages private
foreign and domestic investment, regional autonomy, and local
participation in development."
</P>
<P>
A two-day seminar on ''safety and security for African quality
tourism" will be held during the 4-day meeting. enditem


