<HEADLINE> Mongolia Steps Up Poverty Alleviation Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Mongolian government has
stepped up its efforts to fight against poverty in the country by
setting up a national task force headed by Prime Minister
Mendsaikhan Enkhsaikhan.
</P>
<P>
The task force, known as National Poverty Alleviation
Committee, is aiming at cutting half the population in
poverty by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The committee has the mandate to assist the poor families to
enhance productivities, and receive education and primary health
care services.
</P>
<P>
Enkhsaikhan demanded officials at all levels to attach high
attention to poverty relieving.
</P>
<P>
According to Mongolian National Statistics Bureau, there were
452,400 poor people, or one fifth of the total population, in
Mongolia by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
So far, the government has distributed about 1.2 million
U.S. dollars to the poor through more than 500 programs designed
to increase family earnings, 32 programs on education and 73
others on health care.
</P>
<P>
Over 16,000 people in nearly 2,600 families have benefited from
these activities, of which 6,400 people have acquired jobs and
regular income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
