<HEADLINE> China Gives Lassa Fever Drugs to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 23 (Xinhua) --  Chinese Ambassador Qu Wenming
on Wednesday handed over 40 cartons of Lassa fever drugs to Sierra
Leone Health Minister Mohamed Turay to help combat the growing
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese doctor working in eastern Sierra Leone was among those
who died years ago of the
disease, which is prevalent in the eastern provincial towns of
Kenema, Sebgwema and Tongo.
</P>
<P>
According to Turay, Sierra Leone requested ''emergency
assistance'' from the Chinese Red Cross for the drugs after it was
notified by an American pharmaceutical firm that it was phasing
out production of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
''It was a dilemma until China stepped in and got 120,000
tubes of ribavirini from a medical company in Shangai,'' Turay
added.
</P>
<P>
According to Director General of Medical Services Dr Sheku
Kamara, between January and March this year, about 239 cases of
Lassa fever had been treated and 35 patients died.
</P>
<P>
The disease is traced to bush rats and patients contact the
disease if they eat food contaminated by the rat's urine or with the
blood of an infected patient. enditem


