<HEADLINE> U.S. Reviews International Ban on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States government is
reviewing the total trade ban on elephants and elephant products
imposed by the Convention on International Trade in Endnagered
Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
At the Zimbabwe International Trade Fair held in Bulawayo
today, the country's second largest city, U.S. Ambassador to
Zimbabwe Johnie Carson said his government had no yet come up
with an official policy on the forthcoming CITES conference to be
held in Harare in June.
</P>
<P>
Some African countries are currently calling for the
downlisting of the elephant from CITES' Appendix I which bans
trade in ivory to Appendix II which allows controlled trade.
</P>
<P>
"The review exercise will definitely be over before the
conference begins in June, but this might not necessarily lead to
the change in our policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
All southern African countries now demand the resumption of
the trade of ivory and other elephant products while some western
animal rights groups are trying hard to oppose it, describing the
move as murderous.
</P>
<P>
Carson said he was still consulting with public and interest
groups on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
