<HEADLINE> Demirel Stresses Turkey's Position on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said that the destiny of Turkey and northern Cyprus
were "one and the same", according to the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency report today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Cyprus Flag Radio TV, Demirel pointed
out that there were two different administrations on the divided
island of Cyprus, saying that neither should claim precedence
over the other.
</P>
<P>
Any solution must be based on the realities and justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president added: "This can be achieved only by the
free will of both communities and negotiations between the two
sides on the island. The way can be opened by mutual trust and
constructive relations. A bi-zonal, bi-communal, politically equal
society with Turkey as guarantor is indispensable for a solution."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Russian-made S-300 missiles should not be
BAC157CAB092I23TAQL03:0703:070799
located on the island, adding that Turkey's support for a
U.N. solution did not mean that Turkey could accept the
installation of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Demirel also gave assurances that Turkey's guaranty of Cyprus
would continue and that the security of the island was the same as
the security of any other part of Turkey, as far as Turkey was
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus remains divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island to protect Turkish Cypriots in
the wake of an abortive coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 35,000 Turkish troops are stationed in "the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is only recognized by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
