<HEADLINE> Annan Criticizes Kabila for Stopping Humanitarian Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today criticized Zairean rebel leader Laurent Kabila
for stopping humanitarian aid to the 100,000 Rwandan refugees in
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief urged the international community to press the
rebels to meet their promises previously made to the humanitarian
agencies and allow the passage of the assistance to refugees in
need, whom he said are innocent people.
</P>
<P>
"I think, all of you are aware that assistance is being denied
to 100,000 refugees in Kissangani," Annan told reporters after
briefing the Security Council on the situation in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"I am shocked and appalled by the inhumanity of those who
control this thing in Zaire to these refugees, most of whom are
innocent. I therefore appeal to the entire international community
to work with me in pressing Kabila and those who backed him in the
region, to push him to allow assistance to the refugees," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the international community cannot stand by as
thousands of men and women and children are starving to death.
</P>
<P>
"It is obviously clear if Kabila is in charge of his forces, he
has to bring them under control. If he is not, he should take
measures to control them," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
