<HEADLINE> Iraq Protest Against US Violation of Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraq sent a memo to the Arab
League (AL), protesting against the sustained violation of its
airspace by the warplanes of the United States, France and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
This protest came in the memo to the Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid by Nabiel Negm, Iraqi permanent
delegate to the Cairo-based AL.
</P>
<P>
Iraq demands the three countries to make amends for the
damages they have inflicted on the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with the principle of international
responsibility, Iraq stressed its inalienable legitimate right
for compensation of material and moral damage it sustained as a
recult of this violation," said the memo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Naji al-Hadithi, editor-in-chief of the Baghdad
Observer, today condemned a no-fly zone in southern Iraq as
"clear defiance of international law and the U.N. charter which
unequivocally respect the sovereignty of all nations."
</P>
<P>
In parallel with the U.N. airborne blockade on Iraq after its
August 1990 invasion of Kuwait, the U.S., Britain and France
imposed in August 1991 the no-fly zone in southern Iraq on pretext
to protect Shiite Muslim Iraqis. Since then warplanes from the
three countries patrolled the skies of the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
